<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Throughout this proxy statement, references to the &#147;stock split&#148; relate to the two-for-one stock split of Apache common stock distributed in shares of common
stock on January&nbsp;14, 2004, to shareholders of record on December&nbsp;31, 2003, and references to the &#147;stock dividends&#148; relate to the five-percent stock dividend on Apache common stock distributed in shares of common stock on
April&nbsp;2, 2003, to shareholders of record on March&nbsp;12, 2003, and to the ten-percent stock dividend on Apache common stock distributed in shares of common stock on January&nbsp;21, 2002, to shareholders of record on December&nbsp;31, 2001.
</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:5%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Information on our website is not incorporated by reference into, and does not constitute a part of, this proxy

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>APACHE CORPORATION </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>One Post Oak Central </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Houston, Texas 77056-4400
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">April 3, 2012 </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>PROXY STATEMENT </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_1"></A>GENERAL </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">This proxy statement contains information about the 2012 annual meeting of shareholders of Apache Corporation. In this proxy statement both
&#147;Apache&#148; and the &#147;Company&#148; refer to Apache Corporation. This proxy statement and the enclosed proxy card are being mailed to you by the Company&#146;s Board of Directors starting on or about April 9, 2012. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_2"></A>Purpose of the Annual Meeting </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">At the Company&#146;s annual meeting, shareholders will vote on the following matters: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">On any other business that properly comes before the meeting. As of the date of this proxy statement, the Company is not aware of any other business to
come before the meeting. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">There are no rights of appraisal or similar rights of dissenters arising from matters to be acted
on at the meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_3"></A>Who Can Vote </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Only shareholders of record holding shares of Apache common stock at the close of business on the record date, March&nbsp;26, 2012, are entitled to receive notice of the annual meeting and to vote the
shares of Apache common stock they held on that date. The Company&#146;s stock transfer books will not be closed. A complete list of shareholders entitled to vote at the annual meeting will be available for examination by any Apache shareholder at
2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100, Houston, Texas, for purposes relating to the annual meeting, during normal business hours for a period of ten days before the meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">As of February&nbsp;29, 2012, there were 384,450,172 shares of Apache common stock issued and outstanding. Holders of Apache common stock are entitled to one vote per share and are not allowed to cumulate
votes in the election of directors. The enclosed proxy card shows the number of shares that you are entitled to vote. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_4">
</A>How to Vote </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">If your shares of Apache common stock are held by a broker, bank or other nominee (in &#147;street name&#148;), you will
receive instructions from them on how to vote your shares. If your shares are held by a broker and you do not give the broker specific instructions on how to vote your shares, your broker may vote your shares at its discretion on &#147;routine&#148;
matters. However, your shares will not be voted on any &#147;non-routine&#148; matters to be acted upon at the annual meeting. In such cases, an absence of voting instructions results in a &#147;broker non-vote.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The only &#147;routine&#148; matter to be acted upon at the annual meeting is Item&nbsp;5 &#151; ratification of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the
Company&#146;s independent auditors. All other matters to be acted upon at the annual </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">1 </FONT></P>

not specify how to vote your shares, they will be voted: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">If you are an employee or former employee participating in the Apache 401(k) Savings Plan and have shares of Apache common stock credited to your plan
account as of the record date, such shares are shown on the enclosed proxy card and you have the right to direct the plan trustee regarding how to vote those shares. The trustee for the 401(k) plan is Fidelity Management Trust Company. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The trustee will vote the shares in your plan account in accordance with your instructions. If you do not send instructions (in the manner described under
&#147;How to Vote&#148; above) or if your proxy card is not received by May&nbsp;21, 2012, the shares credited to your account will be voted by the trustee in the same proportion as it votes shares for which it did receive timely instructions.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_6"></A>Revoking a Proxy </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">You may revoke a proxy before it is voted by submitting a new proxy with a later date (by internet, telephone or mail), by voting at the meeting, or by filing a written revocation with Apache&#146;s
corporate secretary. Your attendance at the annual meeting alone will not automatically revoke your proxy. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">2 </FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_7"></A>Quorum </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The presence at the annual meeting, in person or by proxy, of the holders of a majority of the shares of Apache common stock outstanding on the record date will constitute a quorum, permitting the
business of the meeting to be conducted. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_8"></A>Votes Needed </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I><U>Election of Directors</U></I></B><B></B><B><I>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B>In December 2006, the Company&#146;s bylaws were amended to
provide for the election of directors by majority vote. Thus, the affirmative vote of a majority of the votes cast at the annual meeting is required for the election of directors. You may vote FOR or AGAINST any or all director nominees or you may
ABSTAIN as to one or more director nominees. As set forth in our bylaws, only votes FOR or AGAINST the election of a director nominee will be counted. Abstentions and broker non-votes count for quorum purposes, but not for purposes of the election
of directors. A vote to ABSTAIN is not treated as a vote FOR or AGAINST and thus, will have no effect on the outcome of the vote. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I><U>Ratification of the Appointment of Independent Auditors</U>.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The affirmative vote of a majority of the votes cast
at the annual meeting is required for ratification of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors. You may vote FOR or AGAINST the ratification of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors or you
may ABSTAIN. Votes cast FOR or AGAINST and ABSTENTIONS with respect to this matter will be counted as shares entitled to vote on the matter. Broker non-votes will be counted as shares entitled to vote on this matter. A vote to ABSTAIN will have the
effect of a vote AGAINST ratification of the appointment of our independent registered public accounting firm. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I><U>Advisory Vote to
Approve the Compensation of Named Executive Officers</U>.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;You may vote FOR or AGAINST the advisory vote to approve the compensation of our named executive officers or you may ABSTAIN. A majority of the shares of Common
Stock present in person or represented by proxy at our Annual Meeting and entitled to vote must be voted FOR approval of the advisory proposal in order for it to pass. Votes cast FOR or AGAINST and ABSTENTIONS with respect to the proposal will be
counted as shares entitled to vote on the proposal. Broker non-votes will not be counted as shares entitled to vote on the proposal. A vote to ABSTAIN will have the effect of a vote AGAINST the proposal. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I><U>Other Business</U>.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The affirmative vote of a majority of the votes cast at the annual meeting is required for
approval of any other business which may properly come before the meeting or any adjournment thereof. Only votes FOR or AGAINST this proposal will be counted. Abstentions and broker non-votes count for quorum purposes, but not for the voting on this
proposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_9"></A>Who Counts the Votes </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Representatives of Wells Fargo Bank, N.A. will tabulate the votes and act as inspectors of the election. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">3 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_10"></A>ELECTION OF DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>(ITEM NOS. 1-4 ON PROXY CARD) </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company&#146;s certificate of incorporation provides that, as near as numerically possible, one-third of the directors shall be elected at each annual meeting of shareholders. Unless directors earlier
resign or are removed, their terms are for three years, and continue thereafter until their successors are elected and qualify as directors. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The current terms of directors Scott D. Josey, George D. Lawrence, Rodman D. Patton, and Charles J.&nbsp;Pitman will expire at the 2012 annual meeting.
Each of Messrs. Josey, Lawrence, Patton, and Pitman have been recommended by the Company&#146;s Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee and nominated by the Board of Directors for election by the shareholders to an additional three-year term.
If elected, Messrs. Josey, Lawrence, Patton, and Pitman will serve beginning upon election until the annual meeting of shareholders in 2015. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">F. H. Merelli, who served as a director since 1997, retired from the Company&#146;s Board of Directors effective November&nbsp;1, 2011, and Frederick M.
Bohen, who served as a director since 1981, retired from the Company&#146;s Board of Directors on February&nbsp;9, 2012. As a result of these retirements, the size of the Board of Directors was reduced to 12 members. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Unless otherwise instructed, all proxies will be voted in favor of these nominees. If one or more of the nominees is unwilling or unable to serve, the
proxies will be voted only for the remaining named nominees. Proxies cannot be voted for more than four nominees. The Board of Directors knows of no nominee for director who is unwilling or unable to serve. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS RECOMMENDS THAT YOU VOTE &#147;FOR&#148; THE ELECTION OF EACH OF THE DIRECTORS. </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:48px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_11"></A>NOMINEES FOR ELECTION AS DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Biographical information, including principal occupation and business experience during the last five years, of each nominee for director, is set forth below. Unless otherwise stated, the principal
occupation of each nominee has been the same for the past five years. In addition, each nominee&#146;s experience, qualifications, attributes or skills to serve on our Board are discussed under the heading &#147;Qualifications of Directors&#148;
below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>SCOTT D. JOSEY</B>, 54, joined the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in February 2011. Mr.&nbsp;Josey is a director of Northern Tier
Energy LLC, a private downstream energy company, since May 2011, and is a member of its compensation committee. He served as the chairman of the board of Mariner Energy, Inc. from August 2001 until November 2010, when Mariner merged with
Apache.&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Josey was appointed chief executive officer of Mariner in August 2002 and was appointed chief executive officer and president in February 2005. From 2000 to 2002, he served as vice president of Enron North America Corp. and
co-managed its Energy Capital Resources group. From 1995 to 2000, Mr.&nbsp;Josey provided investment banking services to the oil and gas industry and portfolio management services to institutional investors as a co-founder of Sagestone Capital
Partners. From 1993 to 1995, he was a director with Enron Capital&nbsp;&amp; Trade Resources Corp. in its energy investment group. From 1982 to 1993, he worked in all phases of drilling, production, pipeline, corporate planning and commercial
activities at Texas Oil and Gas Corp. At Apache Mr.&nbsp;Josey is a member of the Executive Committee. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">4 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>GEORGE D. LAWRENCE</B>, 61, a private investor, joined the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in May 1996.
Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence was president, chief executive officer, and a director of The Phoenix Resource Companies, Inc., a public oil and gas company, from 1990 until May 1996, when Phoenix merged with Apache. At Apache, he is a member of the Executive
Committee and chairman of the Management Development and Compensation Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>RODMAN D. PATTON</B>, 68, joined the Company&#146;s Board
of Directors in December 1999. Mr.&nbsp;Patton has over 30 years of experience in oil and gas investment banking and corporate finance activity, including serving as managing director of the Merrill Lynch Energy Group from 1993 until April 1999.
Prior to joining Merrill Lynch, he was with The First Boston Corporation (later Credit Suisse First Boston) and Eastman Dillon, Union Securities (later Blyth Eastman Dillon). Mr.&nbsp;Patton is a director of NuStar GP, LLC (formerly Valero GP, LLC),
San Antonio, Texas, and is chairman of its audit committee and a member of its compensation committee. NuStar GP LLC is the general partner of NuStar Energy L.P. (formerly Valero L.P.), owner and operator of crude oil and refined products pipeline,
terminalling, and storage assets. At Apache, Mr.&nbsp;Patton is a member of the Audit Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>CHARLES J. PITMAN</B>, 69, joined the
Company&#146;s Board of Directors in May 2000. Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served as a non-executive director and chairman of Urals Energy Public Company Limited, an oil exploration and production company operating in Russia, from September 2005 until January
2009, chairman of the board of First Calgary Petroleums Ltd., an oil and gas exploration company engaged in exploration and development activities in Algeria, from June 2007 to March 2008, and was sole member of Shaker Mountain Energy Associates LLC
from September 1999 to November 2007. He retired from BP Amoco plc in late 1999, having served as regional president &#151; Middle East/Caspian/Egypt/India. Prior to the merger of British Petroleum and Amoco Corporation in 1998, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman held
a variety of executive positions at Amoco. At Apache, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman is chairman of the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee and a member of the Stock Plan Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_12"></A>CONTINUING DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Biographical information, including
principal occupation and business experience during the last five years, for each continuing member of the Board of Directors whose term is not expiring at the 2012 annual meeting, is set forth below. Unless otherwise stated, the principal
occupation of each director has been the same for the past five years. In addition, each director&#146;s experience, qualifications, attributes or skills to serve on our Board are discussed under the heading &#147;Qualifications of Directors&#148;
below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

cardiovascular surgeon. Dr. Ferlic is the founder of Surgical Services of the Great Plains, P.C. and served as its president from 1974 to 1993. He has been a Regent of the University of Nebraska since November 2000, and was chairman of its audit
committee until March 2008, at which time he became, and continues to serve as, vice chairman. Dr. Ferlic served as a director of the Nebraska Medical Center and chairman of its audit committee from 2004 until his retirement in 2010. He currently
serves as a commissioner and as treasurer for the Midwestern Higher Education Compact, and was elected vice chairman in 2011. At Apache, he is lead director, chairman of the Audit Committee, and a member of the Executive Committee.</FONT></TD>

EnCap Investments L.C., a Dallas, Texas, energy investment banking firm, from 1988 until March 1999, when EnCap was acquired by El Paso Energy. Prior to founding EnCap, Mr. Fiedorek was the managing director of the Energy Banking Group of First

Affiance, Inc., a Georgia - based bank consulting group. In July 2010, Mr. Frazier was appointed chairman of the Special Council for Tax Reform and Fairness to Georgians, established by the Georgia state legislature to examine the state&#146;s tax
code. He served as chairman and chief executive officer of Danka Business Systems PLC, St. Petersburg, Florida, from March 2006 until its sale in July 2008, and was of Counsel with the law firm of Balch &amp; Bingham LLP, Atlanta, Georgia, from
January 2005 to March 2006. From October 2004 until its sale in January 2007, he was a director and chairman of the board of Gold Kist, Inc., Atlanta, Georgia, an integrated chicken production, processing, and marketing company. At Apache, Mr.
Frazier is a member of the Management Development and Compensation Committee and chairman of the Stock Plan Committee.</FONT></TD>

<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>PATRICIA ALBJERG GRAHAM,</B> 76, joined the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in September 2002. Dr. Graham is the Charles Warren Professor of the History of Education, Emerita
at Harvard University. She joined the faculty of Harvard Graduate School of Education in 1974 and served as its dean from 1982 to 1991. From 1991 to 2000, she served as president of the Spencer Foundation, the nation&#146;s leading funder of
research into educational improvement. Dr. Graham is a director of Central European University and Smolny College of St. Petersburg State University, Russia. Dr. Graham also serves as chair of the board of trustees of The Carnegie Foundation for the
Advancement of Teaching and is a member of its compensation committee, having previously served on the Carnegie board from 1984 through 1992. At Apache, she is a member of the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee.</FONT></TD>

Partners, a private equity firm that focuses on investments in the energy and power industries, and is a member of Quantum&#146;s executive and investment committees.&nbsp;Prior to joining Quantum, Mr. Montgomery was a partner in the investment
banking division of Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. from October 2002 to April 2011, where he headed the firm&#146;s Americas Natural Resources Group as well as its Houston office. During his 22 years as an investment banker, Mr. Montgomery focused

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_13"></A>QUALIFICATIONS OF DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In selecting our directors and director nominees, the CG&amp;N Committee has sought to create a board with a broad and balanced set of skills,
complemented by diversity of experience and expertise. As is evidenced by the biographical information set forth above, each director contributes his or her own unique background which has led the CG&amp;N Committee to conclude that the Company and
our shareholders will benefit from the director&#146;s service on the Company&#146;s Board. It is equally important that the particular skill sets of each director complement the experience, qualifications, attributes and skills of our Board of
Directors as a whole. In addition to the qualifications described in the preceding biographical information, the following is a discussion of the particular experience, qualifications, attributes or skills of each director that led our Board to
conclude that he or she will contribute to the diversity of experience and expertise required for the effective functioning of our Board. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>G. STEVEN FARRIS </B>Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; 29 years&#146; experience in the oil and gas industry coupled with his 17 years of direct leadership at
Apache provide him with valuable insight not only into the oil and gas industry, but also the unique day-to-day operations of Apache.&nbsp;Throughout his career, Mr.&nbsp;Farris has held positions of increasing responsibility in the oil and gas
industry, culminating in his appointment as chief executive officer of Apache in May 2002 and chairman of the board in January 2009. Since being named as chief operating officer in 1994, Mr.&nbsp;Farris has been instrumental in growing the
Company&#146;s reserves by eleven times to approximately 3.0 billion barrels of oil equivalent (&#147;boe&#148;) and production to 748,149 boe per day. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>RANDOLPH M. FERLIC </B>Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic has been involved in research activities throughout his professional life, including in-depth analysis of data, probabilities, and risks.&nbsp;For his work as a
cardiovascular and thoracic surgeon, Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic was awarded &#147;Legend&#148; status by the Nebraska Medical Center and, in February 2011, the &#147;Spirit of the Heart&#148; award by the American Heart Association.&nbsp;In addition to
founding Surgical Services of the Great Plains, from 1974 until 1994, Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic served as the corporation&#146;s president, was responsible for and managed its finances, and was trustee and manager of the corporation&#146;s employee benefit
plans. Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic has twice been publicly elected to the University of Nebraska Board of Regents and has served on its audit committee since 2000.&nbsp;He served as a director and executive committee member on the Nebraska Medical Center Board,
a large hospital system, and was chair of the audit committee from January 2004 until retirement in December 2010.&nbsp;Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic was appointed by both Democrat and Republican governors to serve the past 21 years as a commissioner for the
Midwestern Higher Education Compact, a 12-state policy and business compact for all educational activities in those states.&nbsp;He served as treasurer of the Compact from 1997-2000 and again starting in 2010, and was elected vice chairman in
2011.&nbsp;His service to both the Compact and the Nebraska Board of Regents has involved shaping policies that help craft strategic and global views. Over the years, Dr.&nbsp;Ferlic has acquired over 300,000 shares of the Company&#146;s common
stock for himself and his family, which further aligns him with shareholder interests. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>EUGENE C. FIEDOREK </B>After working as a petroleum
reservoir engineer at Shell Oil Company and British American Oil Producing Company for eight years, Mr.&nbsp;Fiedorek spent 37 years in the oil and gas investment banking and commercial banking industries. As co-founder, president, and managing
director of EnCap Investments and managing director of the Energy Banking Group of First RepublicBank, he gained extensive experience in advising oil and gas companies on their capital structure and strategic direction. Through these positions,
Mr.&nbsp;Fiedorek gained valuable experience in identifying, assessing, and minimizing risk that can affect large oil and gas companies. These positions also provided him with the financial reporting expertise necessary for his role on Apache&#146;s
Audit Committee. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">8 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>A. D. FRAZIER, JR. </B>In addition to the many executive positions noted in his biographical information
above, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier spent a large part of his career as an executive in the investment banking industry. He served as the chief executive officer of INVESCO, Inc., an affiliate of an independent global investment management firm, from 1997 to
2000. Mr.&nbsp;Frazier also served as executive vice president, North American Banking Group, of First Chicago Corporation and First National Bank of Chicago from 1982 to 1991, where, among other numerous industry specialties, he oversaw the
Bank&#146;s oil and gas specialty, which provided him with an intimate knowledge of the oil and gas industry. He also served as the chief operating officer of the Atlanta Olympic Games Committee from 1991 to October 1996, and senior advisor to The
Dilenschneider Group, Inc., a New York-based public relations consulting company, during 2011. During his career, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier has been responsible for the development, management, and operation of a diverse group of businesses and
organizations. Through these executive and director positions, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier gathered extensive experience in identifying, analyzing, and managing risk across a wide range of industries. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>PATRICIA ALBJERG GRAHAM </B>Prior to her appointment as dean of Harvard University&#146;s Graduate School of Education in 1982, Dr.&nbsp;Graham served as dean of the Radcliffe Institute, vice president
for Institutional Planning for Radcliffe College, and vice president of Radcliffe College. In 1977, Dr.&nbsp;Graham, a leading historian of American education, left her positions at Radcliffe College upon her appointment by then-President Jimmy
Carter to serve as the director of the National Institute of Education, then the federal government&#146;s education research agency, a position in which she served until 1979. Throughout her career, Dr.&nbsp;Graham has held a variety of leadership
and policy-making roles in the area of education. In her service as dean of Harvard Graduate School of Education and vice president of Radcliffe College, Dr.&nbsp;Graham was responsible for, among other things, the management, structure, and
day-to-day operations of these premiere educational institutions. Dr.&nbsp;Graham also served on the board of Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance Company from 1980 &#151; 2005 and, for most of that period, served on the management compensation and
public policy committee of its board. She was a member of the board of Science Research Associates from 1984 &#151; 1989. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>SCOTT D.
JOSEY</B> Mr.&nbsp;Josey has spent his entire career, spanning over 30 years, in the oil and gas industry.&nbsp;As the former chief executive officer, president, and chairman of the board of Mariner Energy, he gained extensive management, financial,
and technical expertise in the oil and gas field.&nbsp;Through his service in the operations of an oil and gas company, as an investment banker advising the oil and gas industry, and as the chief executive officer of an exploration and production
company, Mr.&nbsp;Josey gained extensive knowledge of an oil and gas company&#146;s prospects and operations and their impact on its financial condition.&nbsp;As an active participant in various energy-related professional organizations, he has an
excellent understanding of the various issues that impact exploration and production companies.&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Josey has invaluable experience in identifying, assessing, and managing risks faced by exploration and production companies like Apache.
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">9 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>CHANSOO JOUNG</B> Mr.&nbsp;Joung has spent almost his entire career working in the finance industry with
energy companies.&nbsp;He currently serves as a senior advisor at Warburg Pincus LLC where he provides advice on new and existing investments in the energy sector.&nbsp;Previously, as a partner at Warburg Pincus, his duties included sourcing,
executing and monitoring energy investments.&nbsp;Prior to joining Warburg Pincus, Mr.&nbsp;Joung spent almost 18 years at Goldman Sachs where he worked in the Natural Resources Group and also founded and led the London-based European Energy Group
in investment banking.&nbsp;While at Warburg Pincus, Mr.&nbsp;Joung served on the boards of a number of private companies in a variety of sectors in the energy industry. He also served on the boards of Targa Resources Corp. and Targa Resources
Partners, LP. Through his experiences as an investment banker, Mr.&nbsp;Joung gained significant experience with energy companies, the energy industry, and energy-related capital markets activity, which enhance his contributions to the
Board.&nbsp;Those experiences have also given Mr.&nbsp;Joung the ability to identify, assess, and manage risk that can affect a large energy company like Apache. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>JOHN A. KOCUR </B>Mr.&nbsp;Kocur was employed by Apache in various roles from the time that the Company&#146;s stock was first listed on the New York Stock Exchange in 1969 until his retirement in
1991. During his tenure, Mr.&nbsp;Kocur served Apache in various roles of increasing responsibility, including serving as its general counsel and culminating in his appointment as the Company&#146;s president in 1979. Mr.&nbsp;Kocur, as president
and later as vice chairman, was instrumental in overseeing Apache&#146;s growth from a small drilling program company into a leading independent, international oil and gas company. Mr.&nbsp;Kocur&#146;s unparalleled experience with and understanding
of the Company&#146;s history and objectives provide invaluable insight into the Company&#146;s past, current, and future operations and management.<B> </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>GEORGE D. LAWRENCE </B>Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence began his oil and gas career with the predecessor to The Phoenix Resource Companies, Inc. in 1985, holding management positions with increasing responsibility,
culminating in his serving as president, chief executive officer, and a director of Phoenix from 1990 until 1996, when the company merged with Apache. During his tenure as chief executive officer of Phoenix, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence gained valuable
corporate leadership experience in all aspects of business including finance, securities, operations, strategy, and&nbsp;risk.&nbsp;At Phoenix and its predecessor, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence was extensively involved in international operations that were
spread over several continents and&nbsp;he was especially instrumental in leading Phoenix&#146;s operations in Egypt, an area that remains at the core of Apache&#146;s operations.&nbsp;Prior to entering the oil and gas business, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence
engaged&nbsp;in a diversified private practice of law and also&nbsp;served five years&nbsp;at the United States Department of Justice, his last position there being the assistant chief of the environmental enforcement section. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>WILLIAM C. MONTGOMERY </B>Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery has spent almost his entire career working in the finance industry focusing on large cap energy
companies.&nbsp;He currently serves as a managing director at Quantum Energy Partners where he provides advice on new and existing investments in the energy and power industries.&nbsp;At Quantum, his duties include membership on the executive and
investment committees, which set the firm&#146;s strategy and originate and oversee investments in the upstream, midstream, and oilfield service sectors of the oil and gas industry.&nbsp;Previously, as a partner at Goldman, Sachs&nbsp;&amp; Co. for
over eight years, he headed the Americas Natural Resources Group and was a member of the Investment Banking Services Leadership Group.&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery&#146;s contributions to the Board will be enhanced by his background as an investment
banker, where he gained significant experience with the energy industry and energy-related capital markets. This experience will also assist him in identifying, assessing, and managing risks faced by large oil and gas companies. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">10 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>RODMAN D. PATTON </B>Prior to joining Apache&#146;s Board of Directors, for over 25 years,
Mr.&nbsp;Patton held various executive positions in the oil and gas investment banking industry. As a managing director at Merrill Lynch, First Boston (later Credit Suisse) and other investment banks, Mr.&nbsp;Patton gained extensive experience
advising oil and gas companies on capital structure, strategy, and direction. He also gained valuable experience in the assessment and management of risk faced by oil and gas companies. As a former investment banker and as chairman of NuStar
GP&#146;s audit committee, Mr.&nbsp;Patton has extensive financial reporting expertise, which serves him well in his role as a member of Apache&#146;s Audit Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>CHARLES J. PITMAN </B>Having served in executive and director capacities at numerous oil and gas companies, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman has gained invaluable experience in and knowledge of the oil and gas
industry. During his 24-year career at Amoco Corporation and BP Amoco plc, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served in a variety of leadership positions in the United States and multiple international locations, principally in the Middle East. Notably,
Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served as president of Amoco Egypt Oil Company from 1992 to 1996, president of Amoco Eurasia Petroleum Company from 1997 to 1998, regional president BP Amoco plc &#151; Middle East/Caspian/Egypt/India from December 1998 until his
retirement in 1999. Most recently, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman has utilized his considerable experience in international oil and gas by participating in oil, gas, and pipeline ventures in Russia, Algeria, and Eastern Europe. Prior to joining Amoco,
Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served in the United States Department of State as a foreign service officer and attorney-adviser. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">11 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_14"></A>DIRECTOR INDEPENDENCE </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">During 2011 and the first two months of 2012, the Board of Directors evaluated all business and charitable relationships between the Company and the
Company&#146;s non-employee directors (all directors other than Mr.&nbsp;Farris) and all other relevant facts and circumstances. As a result of the evaluation, the Board of Directors determined, as required by the Company&#146;s Governance
Principles, that each non-employee director is an independent director as defined by the standards for director independence established by applicable laws, rules, and listing standards including, without limitation, the standards for independent
directors established by The New York Stock Exchange, Inc. (&#147;NYSE&#148;), The NASDAQ National Market (&#147;NASDAQ&#148;), and the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Subject to some exceptions, these standards generally provide that a non-employee director will not be independent if (a)&nbsp;the director is, or in the past three years has been, an employee of the
Company; (b)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is, or in the past three years has been, an executive officer of the Company; (c)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family has received
more than $120,000 per year in direct compensation from the Company other than for service as a director (or for a family member, as a non-executive employee); (d)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is employed as
a partner of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP, the Company&#146;s independent registered public accountants, or the director has an immediate family member who is a current employee of such firm and works in any capacity on the Company&#146;s audit, or
the director or an immediate family member was within the last three years a partner or employee of such firm and personally worked on the Company&#146;s audit within that time; (e)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate
family is, or in the past three years has been, employed as an executive officer of a company where an Apache executive officer serves on the compensation committee; or (f)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is an
executive officer of a company that makes payments to, or receives payments from, Apache in an amount which, in any twelve-month period during the past three years, exceeds the greater of $200,000 or two percent of the consolidated gross revenues of
the company receiving the payment. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Lead Director </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company&#146;s Governance Principles require that the independent (non-employee) directors meet in executive session at least twice each year and, in 2011, they met five times in executive session.
These executive sessions are chaired by a lead director. Pursuant to the Company&#146;s Governance Principles, the lead director is an independent director who is elected from time to time, but not less than annually, by the affirmative vote of a
majority of the non-management directors. In addition to chairing the executive sessions, the lead director discusses management&#146;s proposed meeting agenda with the other independent directors and reviews the approved meeting agenda with our
chairman and chief executive officer, leads the discussion with our chief executive officer following the independent directors&#146; executive sessions, ensures that the Board&#146;s individual group, and committee self-assessments are done
annually, leads periodic discussions with other Board members and management concerning the Board&#146;s information needs, and is available for discussions with major shareholders. Randolph M. Ferlic served as lead director in 2011 and was
re-elected to that position in February 2012. The role and responsibilities of the lead director and the method established for communication of concerns to the independent directors are included in the Company&#146;s Governance Principles, which
are available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">12 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Reporting of Concerns to Independent Directors </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Anyone who has concerns about the Company may communicate those concerns to the independent directors. Such communication should be mailed to the
Company&#146;s corporate secretary at 2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100, Houston, Texas 77056-4400, who will forward such communications to the independent directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Board Leadership Structure and Risk Oversight </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Board Leadership
Structure </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Throughout much of Apache&#146;s history, the Company has ascribed to the traditional U.S. board leadership structure, under
which our chief executive officer has also served as the chairman of our Board of Directors. From 1969 until 2002, both of these positions were held by our founder, Mr.&nbsp;Raymond Plank. However, upon Mr.&nbsp;Raymond Plank&#146;s retirement as
chief executive officer of the Company in 2002, Mr.&nbsp;Farris was appointed as the Company&#146;s chief executive officer and Mr.&nbsp;Raymond Plank remained as the Company&#146;s chairman of the board. Upon Mr.&nbsp;Plank&#146;s retirement as
chairman of the board in January 2009, Mr.&nbsp;Farris was appointed the Company&#146;s chairman of the board, once again unifying the roles of chairman and chief executive officer. As Apache&#146;s history demonstrates, we believe it is important
to maintain the flexibility to have either a combined or a separated chair and CEO structure as circumstances dictate.&nbsp;Each structure has served us well in the past. Currently, we believe that the efficiencies created by a combined position
work best, especially when viewed in conjunction with our lead director, elected annually by our independent directors, assuring strong board leadership.&nbsp;In particular, this structure helps to ensure clarity regarding leadership of the Company,
allows the Company to speak with one voice and provides for efficient coordination of board action, particularly in the event of crisis. The combination of the chairman&#146;s ability to call board meetings with the CEO&#146;s intimate knowledge of
our business, including our risk management framework, provides a strong structure for the efficient operation of our board process and effective leadership of our Board overall. This structure avoids potential confusion as to leadership roles and
duplication of efforts that can result from the roles being separated. It also assists our CEO in managing the Company and dealing with third parties more effectively on a day-to-day basis. Our Board regularly reviews all the aspects of our
governance profile, including this one, and will make changes as circumstances warrant. This is the model that the Company has utilized for much of its history, and we believe that it is the most effective way to lead the Company going forward.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>Risk Oversight </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The goal of the Company&#146;s risk management process is to understand and manage risk; management is responsible for identifying and managing the risks, while directors provide oversight to management
in this process. Management identifies the significant risks facing the Company and the approaches to mitigate such risk. The Company&#146;s Governance Principles state that in addition to its general oversight of management, the Board of Directors
is responsible for a number of specific functions, including assessing major risks facing the Company and reviewing options for their mitigation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our Board of Directors has five standing independent committees: Audit, Corporate Governance and Nominating, Management Development and Compensation, Executive, and Stock Plan. Our Audit Committee is
primarily responsible for overseeing the Company&#146;s risk management processes on behalf of the Board. The Audit Committee charter provides that the Audit Committee should discuss and consider the process by which senior management of the Company
and the relevant departments assess and manage the Company&#146;s exposure to risk, and discuss the Company&#146;s major financial risk exposure and the steps management has taken to monitor, control, and report such exposures. In addition, the
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">13 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">
Audit Committee reports to the Board of Directors, which also considers the Company&#146;s risk profile. The Audit Committee and the Board of Directors obtain input from management regarding the
most significant risks facing the Company and the Company&#146;s risk management strategy. The Audit Committee and the Board ensure that the risks undertaken are consistent with the Board&#146;s tolerance for risk. While the Board is responsible for
setting, monitoring and maintaining the Company&#146;s risk management policies and practices, the Company&#146;s executive officers and members of our management team are responsible for implementing and overseeing our day-to-day risk management
processes. Additionally, the Board has created a Risk Committee composed of members of our management team. The Risk Committee monitors and manages risks related to, among other things, our commodity hedging activities and foreign currency exchange
exposure. The Company believes that this division of responsibility is the most effective way to monitor and control risk. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In addition to the
oversight provided by our full Board of Directors, Audit Committee, executive officers and the members of our management team, including our Risk Committee, our independent (non-employee) directors hold regularly scheduled executive sessions as
often as they deem appropriate, but in any event at least twice each year. These executive sessions are chaired by our lead director, and provide an additional avenue through which we monitor the Company&#146;s risk exposure and policies regarding
risk management. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Risk Considerations in Our Compensation Programs </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our Management Discussion and Compensation (&#147;MD&amp;C&#148;) Committee has discussed the concept of risk as it relates to our compensation programs, and the MD&amp;C Committee does not believe our
compensation programs encourage excessive or inappropriate risk taking. The MD&amp;C Committee, with assistance of its independent compensation consultant (as discussed in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; below), arrived at this
conclusion for the following reasons: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our employees receive both fixed and variable compensation. The fixed (salary) portion provides a steady income regardless of the Company&#146;s stock
performance. This allows executives to focus on the Company&#146;s business without an excessive focus on the Company&#146;s stock price performance. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The goals for the annual cash incentive bonus are set to avoid overweighting any single goal that, if not achieved, would result in the loss of a large
percentage of compensation. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our stock options and restricted stock units generally vest over four years, which discourages short-term risk taking. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our equity ownership requirements encourage a long-term perspective by our executives. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">A substantial portion of our executives&#146; long-term equity compensation is forfeited upon voluntary termination, which encourages our executives to
stay with the Company and maintain a long-term focus. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our incentive programs have been in place for many years, and we have seen no evidence that they encourage excessive risk taking.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Essentially all of our employees participate in our equity-based compensation programs, regardless of business unit which encourages consistent
behavior across the Company. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">14 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_15"></A>STANDING COMMITTEES AND MEETINGS OF THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Board of Directors has an Audit Committee, a Corporate Governance and Nominating (&#147;CG&amp;N&#148;) Committee, an MD&amp;C
Committee, a Stock Plan Committee, and an Executive Committee. Actions taken by these committees are reported to the Board of Directors at the next board meeting. During 2011, each of the Company&#146;s current directors attended at least 75 percent
of all meetings of the Board of Directors and committees of which he or she was a member. During 2011, now-retired directors Bohen and Merelli attended 60 percent and 67 percent, respectively, of all such meetings. Twelve of the thirteen
then-serving directors attended the Company&#146;s 2011 annual meeting of shareholders held on May&nbsp;5, 2011. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" COLSPAN="4" NOWRAP ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Stock</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Option<FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP

<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Stock</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Plan<FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">(1)</SUP></FONT>
