<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Audit Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Audit Committee reviews, with the independent public accountants and internal auditors of the Company, their respective audit and review programs and procedures and the scope and results of their
audits. It also examines professional services provided by the Company&#146;s independent public accountants and evaluates their costs and related fees. Additionally, the Audit Committee reviews the Company&#146;s financial statements and the
adequacy of the Company&#146;s system of internal controls over financial reporting. As described more fully above in &#147;Board Leadership Structure and Risk Oversight,&#148; the Audit Committee is also tasked with overseeing the guidelines,
policies, and controls governing the process by which management of the Company assesses and manages the Company&#146;s exposure to risk. The Audit Committee has the sole authority to appoint, compensate, retain, oversee, and terminate our
independent auditors. It also has the sole authority to pre-approve all terms of and set fees for audit services, audit related services, tax services, and other services to be performed for the Company by the Company&#146;s independent registered
public accountants. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">During 2011 and the first two months of 2012, the Board of Directors reviewed the composition of the Audit Committee
pursuant to the rules of the NYSE and NASDAQ governing audit committees. Based on this review, the Board of Directors confirmed that all members of the Audit Committee are &#147;independent&#148; under the NYSE and NASDAQ rules. In February 2004,
the Audit Committee adopted, and the Board of Directors approved, an amended and restated charter, which reflects the NYSE&#146;s rules and the regulations of the SEC. The Audit Committee charter is available on the Company&#146;s website
(www.apachecorp.com). The Board of Directors has determined that all members of the Audit Committee qualify as financial experts, as defined in Item&nbsp;407 of Regulation S-K under the Securities Act of 1933. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>MD&amp;C Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C
Committee reviews the Company&#146;s management resources and structure and administers the Company&#146;s compensation programs and retirement, stock purchase and similar plans. Under the provisions of its charter, the MD&amp;C Committee may, at
its discretion and if allowed by applicable laws or regulations, delegate all or a portion of its duties and responsibilities to a subcommittee of the MD&amp;C Committee composed of at least two members. During 2011 and the first two months of 2012,
the Board of Directors reviewed the composition of the MD&amp;C Committee pursuant to the rules of the NYSE and NASDAQ governing compensation committees. Based on this review, the Board of Directors confirmed that all members of the MD&amp;C
Committee are &#147;independent&#148; under the NYSE and NASDAQ rules. The MD&amp;C Committee charter is available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>CG&amp;N Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The duties of the CG&amp;N Committee include recommending to the Board
of Directors the slate of director nominees submitted to the shareholders for election at each annual meeting and proposing qualified candidates to fill vacancies on the Board of Directors. The CG&amp;N Committee is also responsible for developing
corporate governance principles for the Company, reviewing related party transactions, and overseeing the evaluation of the Board of Directors. During 2011 and the first two months of 2012, the Board of Directors reviewed the composition of the
CG&amp;N Committee pursuant to the rules of the NYSE and NASDAQ governing nominating and governance committees. Based on this review, the Board of Directors confirmed that all members of the CG&amp;N Committee are &#147;independent&#148; under the
NYSE and NASDAQ rules. The CG&amp;N Committee charter is available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The CG&amp;N Committee
considers director nominee recommendations from executive officers of the Company, independent members of the Board and shareholders of the Company, as well as recommendations from other interested parties. The CG&amp;N Committee may also retain an
outside </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">16 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">
search firm to assist it in finding appropriate nominee candidates. Shareholder recommendations for director nominees received by Apache&#146;s corporate secretary (at the address for submitting
shareholder proposals and nominations set forth under the heading &#147;Future Shareholder Proposals and Director Nominations&#148; below) are forwarded to the CG&amp;N Committee for consideration. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Stock Plan Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In July 2011, the
Board of Directors formed a fifth standing independent committee, the Stock Plan Committee, to replace the Stock Option Plan Committee, which was a subcommittee of the MD&amp;C Committee. The Stock Plan Committee charter is available on the
Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). The principal purpose of the stock plan committee is to assist the Board of Directors in the discharge of its responsibilities related to equity-based compensation for the Company&#146;s employees,
including the named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The three members of the Stock Plan Committee are &#147;outside directors&#148; as defined by
applicable federal tax law or regulations of the Internal Revenue Service. The duties of the Stock Plan Committee include (i)&nbsp;administration of the Company&#146;s equity-based compensation plans and programs and approval, award, and
administration of grants made thereunder, (ii)&nbsp;certification of performance goals and their achievement, (iii)&nbsp;making recommendations to the Board of Directors with respect to the Company&#146;s equity-based compensation plans and
programs, and (iv)&nbsp;any other duties and responsibilities expressly delegated to the Stock Plan Committee by the Board of Directors relating to equity-based compensation plans and programs. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Executive Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Executive
Committee is vested with the authority to exercise the full power of the Board of Directors, within established policies, in the intervals between meetings of the Board of Directors. In addition to the general authority vested in it, the Executive
Committee may be vested with specific powers and authority by resolution of the Board of Directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Committee Charters </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">As noted above, you can access electronic copies of the charters of the Audit Committee, CG&amp;N Committee, MD&amp;C Committee, and Stock Plan Committee
of the Board of Directors on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). Also available on the Company&#146;s website are our Governance Principles and our Code of Business Conduct, which meets the requirements of a code of ethics under
applicable SEC regulations and NYSE and NASDAQ standards. You may request printed copies of any of these documents by writing to Apache&#146;s corporate secretary at 2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100, Houston, Texas 77056-4400. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">17 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_16"></A>CRITERIA FOR NEW BOARD MEMBERS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>AND RE-ELECTION OF BOARD MEMBERS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The CG&amp;N Committee considers the following criteria in recommending new nominees or the re-election of directors to the Company&#146;s Board of Directors and its committees: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Expertise and perspective needed to govern the business and strengthen and support senior management &#151; for example: strong financial expertise,
knowledge of international operations, or knowledge of the petroleum industry and/or related industries. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Sound business judgment and a sufficiently broad perspective to make meaningful contributions. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Interest and enthusiasm in the Company and a commitment to become involved in its future. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The time and energy to meet Board of Directors commitments. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Ability to constructively participate in discussions, with the capacity to quickly understand and evaluate complex and diverse issues.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Dedication to the highest ethical standards. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Supportive of management, but independent, objective, and willing to question and challenge both openly and in private exchanges.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">An awareness of the dynamics of change and a willingness to anticipate and explore opportunities. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">All decisions to recommend the nomination of a new nominee for election to the Board of Directors or for the re-election of a director are within the sole
discretion of the CG&amp;N Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">All director candidates are evaluated, and the decision of whether or not to nominate a particular
candidate is made, based solely on Company- and work-related factors and not with regard to a candidate&#146;s or director&#146;s inclusion in any protected class or group identified in the Company&#146;s anti-discrimination policy. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The above criteria and guidelines, together with the section of the Company&#146;s Governance Principles entitled &#147;Qualifications of Board
Members&#148; constitute the policy of the CG&amp;N Committee regarding the recommendation of new nominees or the re-election of directors to the Company&#146;s Board of Directors or its committees. The Company&#146;s Governance Principles are
available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Diversity </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Company policy precludes directors and employees from discriminating against any protected group.&nbsp;Company policy also precludes directors and employees from basing work-related decisions on anything
other than work-relevant criteria.&nbsp;The Company&#146;s approach to diversity complements these policies without conflicting with them. Our status as a global company makes the need for board diversity in all its aspects essential to our
business.&nbsp;Our criteria for board selection, summarized in this section, operates as our diversity policy. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">18 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_17"></A>REPORT OF THE AUDIT COMMITTEE </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><I>The following report of the Audit Committee of the Company shall not be deemed to be &#147;soliciting material&#148; or to be &#147;filed&#148; with
the Securities and Exchange Commission, nor shall this report be incorporated by reference into any filing made by the Company under the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, or the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended. </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Audit Committee oversees the Company&#146;s financial reporting process on behalf of the Board of Directors. The Company&#146;s management has the
primary responsibility for preparing the financial statements, maintaining effective internal controls over financial reporting, and assessing the effectiveness of internal controls over financial reporting. In fulfilling its oversight
responsibilities, the Audit Committee reviewed and discussed the audited consolidated financial statements in the Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011 with Company management, including a discussion of the quality,
not just the acceptability, of the accounting principles, the reasonableness of significant judgments, and the clarity of disclosures in the financial statements. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Audit Committee reviewed with the independent registered public accounting firm, which is responsible for expressing an opinion on the conformity of those audited consolidated financial statements
with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles, its judgments as to the quality, not just the acceptability, of the Company&#146;s accounting principles and such other matters as are required to be discussed with the Audit Committee by Statement
on Auditing Standards No.&nbsp;61, <I>Communication with Audit Committees,</I> as amended and as adopted by the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board in Rule 3200T. In addition, the Audit Committee has discussed with the independent registered
public accounting firm the firm&#146;s independence from Company management and the Company, including the matters in the letter from the firm required by PCAOB Rule 3526, <I>Communication with Audit Committees Covering Independence</I>, and
considered the compatibility of non-audit services with the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s independence. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Audit
Committee also reviewed management&#146;s report on its assessment of the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal controls over financial reporting as well as the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s report on the effectiveness
of the Company&#146;s internal controls over financial reporting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Audit Committee discussed with the Company&#146;s internal auditors and
independent registered public accounting firm the overall scope and plans for their respective audits. At each of the five Audit Committee meetings held in person during 2011, the Audit Committee met with the internal auditors and the independent
registered public accounting firm, with and without management present, to discuss the results of their examinations, their evaluations of the Company&#146;s internal controls, including internal controls over financial reporting, and the overall
quality of the Company&#146;s financial reporting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In reliance on the reviews and discussions referred to above, the Audit Committee
recommended to the Board of Directors, and the Board has approved, that the audited consolidated financial statements and management&#146;s assessment of the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal controls over financial reporting be included
in the Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011, filed by the Company with the Securities and Exchange Commission. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">19 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Audit Committee is governed by a charter, which is available on the Company&#146;s website
(www.apachecorp.com). The Audit Committee held eight meetings during fiscal year 2011, including the five in-person meetings referenced above. The Audit Committee is comprised solely of independent directors as defined by the New York Stock Exchange
and the NASDAQ National Market listing standards and Rule 10A-3 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="55%"> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:1px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">February&nbsp;15, 2012 </FONT></P></TD>
<TD><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Members of the Audit Committee </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:55%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Randolph M. Ferlic,
Chairman </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:55%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Eugene C. Fiedorek </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:55%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Chansoo Joung </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:55%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Rodman D. Patton </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_18"></A>DIRECTOR COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Non-Employee Directors&#146; Cash Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">During 2011, under the terms of the
non-employee directors&#146; compensation plan, each non-employee director received an annual cash retainer of $150,000 (with no separate meeting attendance fees or retainer payable in shares), and the chairman of each committee received an
additional annual cash retainer of $15,000 for chairing that committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">During 2011, under the terms of the Company&#146;s non-employee
directors&#146; compensation plan, non-employee directors could defer receipt of all or any portion of their cash retainers. Deferred cash amounts accrue interest equal to the Company&#146;s rate of return on its short-term marketable securities.
Once each year, participating directors may elect to transfer all or a portion of their deferred cash amounts into the form of shares of Apache common stock. After such election, amounts deferred in the form of Apache common stock accrue dividends
as if the stock were issued and outstanding when such dividends were payable. All deferred amounts, as well as accrued interest and dividends, are maintained in a separate memorandum account for each participating non-employee director. Amounts are
paid out in cash and/or shares of Apache common stock, as applicable, upon the non-employee director&#146;s retirement or other termination of his or her directorship, or on a specific date, in a lump sum or in annual installments over a ten-year
(or shorter) period. One non-employee director deferred all of his cash retainer fees during 2011. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Non-Employee Directors&#146; Restricted
Stock Units Program </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In May 2011, the Company established the Non-Employee Directors&#146; Restricted Stock Units Program (the &#147;RSU
Program&#148;), pursuant to the Company&#146;s 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan. Each year, all non-employee directors are eligible to receive grants of restricted stock units the number of which is calculated by dividing $200,000 by the fair
market value of a share of Apache common stock on the date of grant. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Each non-employee director was awarded 1,897 restricted stock units on
August&nbsp;15, 2011 under the RSU Program, with a grant date fair value of $199,982. Half of the restricted stock units vest thirty days after the grant and the other half vest on the one-year anniversary date of the grant. Each restricted stock
unit is equivalent to one share of common stock. Except as noted below, any unvested restricted stock units are forfeited at the time the non-employee director ceases to be a member of the Board. The unvested portion of any award automatically vests
upon death or termination without cause (including retirement). Non-employee directors are required to choose, at the time of each award, whether such award will vest as 100 percent common stock or a combination of 40 percent cash and 60 percent
common stock. Additionally, non-employee directors are entitled to receive dividend equivalents, equal to dividends on the Company&#146;s common stock, in cash on the unvested portions of the restricted stock unit awards. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">20 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Equity Compensation Plan for Non-Employee Directors </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company established an equity compensation plan for non-employee directors in February 1994, which is administered by the MD&amp;C Committee. The
original expiration date for this plan was July&nbsp;1, 2009, with a maximum of 50,000 shares of common stock (115,500 shares after adjustment for the stock dividends and stock split) for awards granted during the term of the plan. However, in
February 2007, the plan was amended to provide that no new awards would be granted subsequent to January&nbsp;1, 2007, and no awards have been made since that date. The plan continues in existence solely for the purpose of governing
still-outstanding awards made prior to January&nbsp;1, 2007. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Each non-employee director was awarded 1,000 restricted shares of the
Company&#146;s common stock every five years from July&nbsp;1, 1994 through July&nbsp;1, 2000, with the shares vesting at a rate of 200 shares annually. On May&nbsp;3, 2001, the plan was amended to provide that on July&nbsp;1, 2001 and on
July&nbsp;1 of each third year thereafter, each non-employee director was awarded 1,000 restricted shares of common stock, with one-third of the shares vesting annually. On February&nbsp;5, 2004, the plan was amended to adjust the awards to 2,310
restricted shares of common stock (1,000 shares adjusted for the stock dividends and stock split) for any awards made on July&nbsp;1, 2004 and thereafter. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Awards were made from shares of common stock held in the Company&#146;s treasury and were automatic and non-discretionary. All shares awarded under the plan have vested, have full dividend and voting
rights, and are not eligible for sale while the non-employee director is still serving as a member of the Board. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Share Ownership
Requirement </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company has a minimum share ownership requirement for non-employee directors. Within three years of joining the Board,
each non-employee director is required to directly own shares and/or share equivalents totaling at least 7,000 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock. Non-employee directors must continue to meet the minimum share ownership requirement while
serving on the Board. As of the date of this proxy statement, each non-employee director directly owned shares and/or share equivalents totaling more than 7,000 shares of the Company&#146;s common stock. See beneficial ownership information under
the heading &#147;Securities Ownership and Principal Holders&#148; below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Outside Directors&#146; Retirement Plan </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">An unfunded retirement plan for non-employee directors was established in December 1992, and amended most recently in July 2011. The plan is administered
by the MD&amp;C Committee and, for directors who retired prior to July&nbsp;21, 2011, paid retired non-employee directors benefits equal to two-thirds (2/3)&nbsp;of the annual retainer for a period based on length of service. For non-employee
directors retiring after July&nbsp;21, 2011, the plan generally pays an annual benefit equal to 100 percent of the retired director&#146;s annual retainer for a period based on length of service. Payments are made either (i)&nbsp;on a quarterly
basis, for a maximum of ten years, or (ii)&nbsp;in a single lump sum equal to the net present value of the quarterly payments to which the director is entitled, and are paid from the general assets of the Company. In the event of the director&#146;s
death prior to receipt of all benefits payable under the plan, the remaining benefits are payable to the director&#146;s surviving spouse or designated beneficiary until the earlier of the termination of the payment period or the death of the
surviving spouse or designated beneficiary. During 2011, benefits were paid under this plan to one former director who retired from the Company&#146;s Board of directors in November 2011. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">21 </FONT></P>

(ii)&nbsp;the principal executive officer, the principal financial officers, and the three other most highly compensated executive officers who served as officers of the Company during 2011, and (iii)&nbsp;all directors and executive officers of the
Company as a group. All ownership information is based upon filings made by those persons with the SEC and upon information provided to the Company. (All share numbers in the table and footnotes have been adjusted for the stock dividends and stock
split.) </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_20"></A>SECTION 16(a) BENEFICIAL OWNERSHIP REPORTING COMPLIANCE </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, requires the Company&#146;s directors and officers, as well as beneficial owners of
ten percent or more of the Company&#146;s common stock, to report their holdings and transactions in the Company&#146;s securities. Based on information furnished to the Company and contained in reports provided pursuant to Section&nbsp;16(a), as
well as written representations that no other reports were required for 2011, the Company&#146;s directors and officers timely filed all reports required by Section&nbsp;16(a), with the exception of a late report filed by Scott D.&nbsp;Josey.
</FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_22"></A>EXECUTIVE OFFICERS OF THE COMPANY </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Biographical information for the executive officers of the Company is set forth below. Biographical information for G. Steven Farris is set forth above
under the caption &#147;Continuing Directors.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>MICHAEL S. BAHORICH, </B>55, was appointed executive vice president and chief
technology officer in November 2010, having previously served as the Company&#146;s executive vice president and technology officer since February 2009, executive vice president &#151; exploration and production technology since May 2000, vice
president &#151; exploration and production technology since January 1999, vice president &#151; exploration technology since December 1997, and chief geophysicist since 1996. From 1981 until joining the Company in 1996, he held positions of
increasing responsibility at Amoco Corporation in Denver, Colorado and Tulsa, Oklahoma. Mr.&nbsp;Bahorich is a member of the board of trustees of the Houston Museum of Natural Science and serves on advisory boards at Stanford University and Yale
University. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>JOHN R. BEDINGFIELD, </B>56, was appointed vice president &#151; worldwide exploration and new ventures in November 2009. He
previously served as the Company&#146;s regional vice president and managing director for the Australia region since May 2009, deputy managing director &#151; exploration for the Australia region since August 2005, region exploration manager for the
Egypt region since 2003, geophysical manager for Egypt since 1999, and senior staff geophysicist since 1998. Prior to joining the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Bedingfield was employed by Exxon Corporation from 1982 to 1998 in a variety of U.S. domestic and
international assignments. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>THOMAS P. CHAMBERS, </B>56, was appointed executive vice president and chief financial officer in November 2010,
having previously served as the Company&#146;s vice president &#151; corporate planning and investor relations since March 2009, vice president &#151; corporate planning since September 2001, and director of corporate planning since March 1995.
Prior to joining the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Chambers was in the international business development group at Pennzoil Exploration and Production, having held a variety of management positions with the BP plc group of companies from 1981 to 1992.
Mr.&nbsp;Chambers is a member of the Society of Petroleum Engineers and serves on the advisory board of Houston Foundation for Life. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>MATTHEW W. DUNDREA, </B>58, was appointed senior vice president &#151; treasury and administration in November 2010, having previously served as the
Company&#146;s vice president and treasurer since July 1997, treasurer since March 1996, and assistant treasurer since 1994. Prior to joining the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Dundrea held positions of increasing responsibility at Union Texas Petroleum Holding,
Inc. from 1982 to 1994. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>ROBERT J. DYE, </B>56, was appointed senior vice president &#151; global communications and corporate affairs in
November 2010. He previously served as the Company&#146;s vice president &#151; corporate services since March 2009, vice president &#151; investor relations since May 1997, director of investor relations since 1995, and held positions of increasing
responsibility in the Company&#146;s corporate planning area since 1992. Prior to joining the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Dye was planning manager for the offshore division of BP Exploration, Houston, Texas, from 1988 to 1992. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>RODNEY J. EICHLER, </B>62, was appointed president and chief operating officer in February 2011. He previously served as the Company&#146;s co-chief
operating officer and president &#151; international since February 2009, executive vice president &#151; Egypt since February 2003, regional vice president in Egypt since 1999, and vice president of exploration and production in Egypt since 1997.
Mr.&nbsp;Eichler also served as regional vice president for the Western region in Houston since 1996 and regional exploration and development manager for the Rocky Mountain region in Denver since 1993. Prior to joining the Company, he was vice
president &#151; exploration for Axem Resources, LLC in Denver, Colorado, from 1989 to 1993. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">26 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>DAVID L. FRENCH, </B>42, was appointed vice president &#151; business development in January 2010, having
previously served as region production manager &#151; west for Apache Canada in Calgary, Alberta, since 2007. Mr.&nbsp;French also held positions of increasing responsibility, including production engineering manager and director of purchasing,
EH&amp;S and general services since joining Apache in 2005. Prior to joining the Company, he served as an associate principle for McKinsey&nbsp;&amp; Company, a global management consulting firm, and held engineering and planning management roles in
the Permian Basin for Amoco and Altura Energy Ltd. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>JON A. GRAHAM</B>, 57, was appointed vice president &#151; environmental, health and
safety in May 2011, having served as the Company&#146;s region vice president and country manager in Argentina since June 2009. He joined the company in 1994 as reservoir engineering manager in the Rockies Region. He was also vice president for
reservoir engineering in Canada, reservoir engineering manager for the Western and Gulf of Mexico regions, Gulf Coast Onshore Region vice president, and engineering general manager for Apache Egypt Companies. Prior to joining Apache, he was
associated with Hunt Oil Co., Pacific Enterprises Oil Co., Santa Fe Minerals, and Amoco. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>RODNEY A. GRYDER, </B>63, was appointed vice
president, audit in November 2010. He previously served as the Company&#146;s director, internal audit and business analysis since December 2001 and director, internal audit since 1998. Prior to joining Apache, Mr.&nbsp;Gryder was the director of
corporate audit services at Western Atlas, Inc., manager of internal audit at TransTexas Gas Corporation, finance manager at Occidental International Exploration&nbsp;&amp; Production, and held various audit positions at Tenneco Oil
Exploration&nbsp;&amp; Production. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>MARGERY M. HARRIS</B>, 51, was appointed executive vice president &#151; human resources in December
2011, having been senior vice president &#151; human resources since February 2011, and vice president &#151; human resources since September 2007. Prior to joining the Company, she was consultant/principal of MMH Consulting Services, a
privately-held human resources consulting firm, from 2006 to September 2007, executive vice president and senior vice president &#151; human resources with Texas Genco LLC, a wholesale power generator, from 2005 to 2006, and senior vice president
&#151; human resources and administration of Integrated Electrical Services, Inc., from 2000 to 2005. Ms.&nbsp;Harris worked for Santa Fe Snyder (successor to Santa Fe Energy Resources) from 1995 to 2000 in a variety of human resources capacities,
including vice president &#151; human resources. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>REBECCA A. HOYT, </B>47, was appointed vice president, chief accounting officer, and
controller in November 2010. She previously served as the Company&#146;s vice president and controller since November 2006, assistant controller since 2003, and held positions of increasing responsibility within the accounting area since joining the
Company in 1993. Previously, Ms.&nbsp;Hoyt was an audit manager with Arthur Andersen LLP, an independent public accounting firm, from 1992 to 1993. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>JON A. JEPPESEN, </B>64, was appointed executive vice president &#151; Gulf of Mexico regions in May 2011, having been executive vice president since August 2009, senior vice president since February
2003, regional vice president for the Gulf Coast region since 2002, and regional vice president for the Offshore region since 1996. He served as the Company&#146;s vice president of exploration and development for North America from 1994 to 1996,
and exploration and development manager of the Offshore region from 1993 to 1994. Prior to joining the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen was vice president of exploration and development for Pacific Enterprises Oil Company, Dallas, Texas, from 1989 to
1992. </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_23"></A>COMPENSATION DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>OVERVIEW OF THE YEAR 2011 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Apache&#146;s
57th year was exceptional on a number of fronts. Beginning with the challenge of integrating over $11 billion of assets acquired in 2010 and introducing 850 new employees to Apache&#146;s unique culture and core business values, the year ended with
the setting of a number of important records. We invested an unprecedented $8 billion of E&amp;D capital and drilled 1,087 gross wells across Apache&#146;s ten operating regions in six different countries. These new investments generated returns
that exceeded Company internal rate of return targets for each of our regions and contributed to record production, earnings, and cash from operations. As a result, the Company was able to fund this active drilling campaign and spend an additional
$1.8 billion in acquisitions, out of internally generated cash flow, while reducing debt by $925 million, thereby enhancing Apache&#146;s financial flexibility. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Apache&#146;s 2011 financial and operational highlights include: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Record oil and gas revenues of $16.8 billion, a 38 percent increase over 2010; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">
Committee. In addition, two directors retired: former Audit and Executive Committee member F. H. Merelli retired in November 2011, and Frederick M. Bohen, the former chairman of the MD&amp;C
Committee and the Stock Plan Committee, retired in February 2012. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Further, Apache was recognized as one of Fortune Magazine&#146;s Most
Admired Companies for 2012, receiving one of the highest scores in the Mining, Crude Oil Production category of companies. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>EXECUTIVE
COMPENSATION DECISION MAKING PROCESSES </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Role of the Board of Directors </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our Board of Directors believes that compensation decision making is both a core Board responsibility and an effective tool for shaping the Company&#146;s strategy and performance. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>The Management Development and Compensation Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C Committee plays a key role in the Board&#146;s compensation oversight and decision making. In November 2011, Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery joined the MD&amp;C Committee, and in February 2012,
Mr.&nbsp;Bohen, retired from the Board. Each of the MD&amp;C Committee&#146;s four members meets the independence requirements of the New York Stock Exchange and NASDAQ listing standards. The MD&amp;C Committee&#146;s charter is posted on the
Company&#146;s website. The Committee met seven times in 2011. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C Committee, on behalf of the Board of Directors, is responsible for
reviewing and assessing the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s compensation programs, in general, and its executive compensation programs, in particular. In performing these duties, the Committee reviews compensation programs and policies to avoid
the incentivizing of excessive risk. Compensation responsibility includes oversight and review of the base salary, annual cash incentive bonus, long-term compensation, and benefit programs for the Company&#146;s executive officers. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C Committee&#146;s key responsibilities are: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">To review the Company&#146;s goals and objectives, evaluate performance in light of such goals, and recommend the chairman and chief executive
officer&#146;s compensation to the Board for approval by the independent directors. This review is handled in independent sessions. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">To make recommendations to the Board concerning the base salary, incentive and equity-based compensation plans for executive officers other than the
chairman and chief executive officer. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">To review and recommend to the Board broad-based, long-term compensation programs for executive and non-executive employees.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Board and the MD&amp;C Committee have broad access to information to perform their compensation functions. The Board has
authorized the Committee to retain an independent compensation consultant. In 2011, the Committee retained Pearl Meyer&nbsp;&amp; Partners (the &#147;Consultant&#148;) to provide independent compensation advice and data to the MD&amp;C Committee and
the Board. Except for limited work for management in connection with the Consultant&#146;s published industry-specific surveys, for which the Consultant received <I>de minimis</I> compensation, the Consultant did not provide any services to the
Company other than the executive compensation-related services to the Board. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In addition to the use of an independent consultant, the MD&amp;C
Committee receives compensation recommendations and evaluations of the executive group from the chairman and chief executive officer. The MD&amp;C Committee, along with each of the Company&#146;s independent directors, is authorized by the Board to
obtain information from and work directly with any member of the senior executive team in fulfilling its responsibilities. The Company&#146;s executive vice president of human resources prepares information and materials for the chairman and chief
executive officer and the MD&amp;C Committee for the exercise of their distinct, but interrelated, compensation responsibilities. The MD&amp;C Committee </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">31 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">
also utilizes the data provided by the Consultant, including recommendations for the associated values or salary levels derived from their reports. The Committee carefully considers the chairman
and chief executive officer&#146;s recommendations on these matters, reaches final determination, and reports these outcomes to the Board of Directors in the form of recommended actions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Compensation Philosophy </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Our compensation philosophy is designed to attract, retain, motivate and reward top talent. Our forfeiture provisions encourage retention and deter
excessive risk taking. Our long-standing practice of awarding equity-based pay to substantially all employees reflects our view that each and every employee has the opportunity to contribute to the overall success of the Company. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">At Apache&#146;s 2011 annual meeting of shareholders, the Company&#146;s shareholders overwhelmingly approved the compensation of our named executive
officers for fiscal 2010, with over 94 percent of shareholder votes cast were in favor such compensation. Our compensation program, which includes equity holding requirements for officers and directors, our total shareholder return program using
rolling three-year performance and five-year vesting time frames, and our payment of 60 percent of our named executive officers&#146; compensation in equity-based forms, reflects our belief in paying for on-going long-term performance and aligning
employee and shareholder interests. As a result of our shareholders&#146; approval of the compensation of our named executive officers for fiscal 2010, the Board decided to continue to adhere to the Company&#146;s pay-for-performance philosophy in
2011 and did not materially change our executive compensation decisions and policies. Going forward, the MD&amp;C Committee and the Board will continue to review our executive compensation program and consider the views of our shareholders with
respect thereto. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Use of an Industry Peer Group and Survey Data </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Board of Directors believes that both data and judgment play important roles in the design and implementation of optimal compensation programs. The MD&amp;C Committee, the Consultant, and senior
executives consider multiple sources of internal and external data in making individual and plan-level compensation decisions. In each section of this Compensation Discussion and Analysis dealing with an individual element of compensation, data
relevant to that element is discussed. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Peer group data plays an important role in our compensation decision making. For its 2011 compensation
analysis, the MD&amp;C Committee considered a peer group comprised of the companies that we most often compete with for executive talent. The companies in this group, for the large part, have North American oil and/or natural gas businesses and are
comparable based on relevant financial factors, such as revenue, market capital, net income, and total assets. Our peer group for 2011 (the &#147;2011 Compensation Peer Group&#148;) comprised: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In addition to the 2011 Compensation Peer Group, the MD&amp;C Committee has also created a broader peer
group that it uses in connection with the Company&#146;s total shareholder return program (&#147;TSR Program&#148;). For additional information on the Company&#146;s TSR Program, please see &#147;Long Term Compensation &#151; Performance Shares
&#151; Total Shareholder Return Program&#148; below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In addition to the 2011 Compensation Peer Group data, the MD&amp;C Committee uses the
latest available data provided by the Consultant from published energy-sector surveys and from published, general industry size-based surveys. The MD&amp;C Committee reviews the Consultant&#146;s benchmarking data and its process for assimilating
the data used in this competitive benchmarking process, which is a blend of data from our 2011 Compensation Peer Group and the applicable survey data. Additionally, we review Fortune 500 proxy data for companies with market caps similar to ours to
compare the compensation of the named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Use of Judgment </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Board of Directors and the MD&amp;C Committee believe that the application of their collective experiences and related business judgment is as important to the compensation decision process as is the
application of data and formulae. The Company&#146;s compensation policies and practices reflect this belief. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">While market data provide an
important tool for analysis and decision-making, the MD&amp;C Committee and the Board realize that over-reliance on data can give a false illusion of precision. Consequently, the MD&amp;C Committee and the Board also give consideration to an
individual&#146;s personal contributions to the organization, as well as his or her skill sets, qualifications, experience, and demonstrated performance. The MD&amp;C Committee and the Board also value and seek to reward performance that develops
talent within the Company, embraces the sense of urgency that defines the Company, and demonstrates the qualities of imagination and drive that enable an Apache officer to resolve longer-term challenges or important new issues. These and similar
qualities and competencies are not easily correlated to typical compensation data, but also deserve, and are given, consideration in reaching compensation decisions. The market data provides the MD&amp;C Committee and senior management with the
foundation for application of the above principles and the ensuing decisions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Four Key Compensation Elements </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company&#146;s executive compensation program has four parts: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Base salary; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Annual cash incentive bonus; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Long-term compensation; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Benefits. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">We generally
target base salaries to fall between the 50th and 75th percentile of the market data. Annual and long-term incentive plans are initially targeted as a function of base salaries and are designed to produce total compensation (base salary, annual cash
incentive bonus, plus annual long-term compensation awards) between the 50th and 75th percentile of the market data. We do not have a specific formula that dictates the overall weighting of each element as a part of total compensation. We constantly
review and modify our benefits programs to ensure that we provide competitive benefits to our employees. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The market for talent in our industry
is tight. To ensure the Company&#146;s continued success, we must attract and retain superior talent in this competitive market. This requires that we maintain a competitive and attractive compensation environment at all levels of the Company.

grant date fair value for the 2011 annual equity awards. For a discussion of the 2011 compensation of the named executive officers, see &#147;Compensation Decisions in 2011&#148; below. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:6%">


<IMG SRC="g300104g33t10.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The charts above illustrate that 88 percent of our chairman and chief executive officer&#146;s total direct
compensation, and 86 percent of our other named executive officers&#146; total direct compensation, is variable and that 56 percent of our chairman and chief executive officer&#146;s total direct compensation, and 71 percent of our other named
executive officers&#146; total direct compensation, is equity-based long-term compensation that rewards them only when our shareholders are also rewarded. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Compensation Elements </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Base Salary </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">A competitive base salary for each of our employees is essential to our ability to compete. To review and recommend base salary ranges, the MD&amp;C
Committee analyzes the compensation for each executive officer position by: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Examining the scope of the job, the nature and complexity of the responsibilities, the financial impact of the position, the training, knowledge, and
experience required to perform the job, the recruiting challenges and opportunities associated with the position, the risks and opportunities associated with hiring at the higher and lower ranges of the position skill sets, the expected autonomy of
the job, and, for current executives, the Company-specific experience, seniority, performance, and compatibility. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Utilizing energy-industry and company-size general surveys to establish salary ranges for comparable executives, where the mid-point of the range
reflects the 50th percentile of the market data. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Evaluating the executive positions on the basis of these factors. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>

<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Using their judgment to determine where a particular executive&#146;s salary falls within the salary ranges. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">34 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C Committee reviews base salaries periodically (typically every 12 to 18 months). Base salary
reviews may occur more or less frequently depending on Company and market conditions and individual performance. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Annual Cash Incentive
Bonus </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company&#146;s executive officers are eligible to earn an annual cash incentive bonus tied to a combination of each
officer&#146;s individual achievement of job-specific goals and the Company&#146;s achievement of a variety of financial, operational, and management objectives, which we refer to as corporate performance goals and corporate management objectives,
respectively. The corporate performance goals are a set of objective standards that are set at the beginning of each year in respect of production growth, reserve growth, earnings, cash flow, and lifting costs per boe. These goals are modified from
time to time by the MD&amp;C Committee to appropriately reflect acquisitions, dispositions, and other major events. Our corporate management objectives include a long list of tactical goals developed and weighted by management, and approved by the
MD&amp;C Committee, at the beginning of each year. These objectives are then modified through the year as circumstances dictate and as approved by the MD&amp;C Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Corporate Performance and Related Bonus Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The MD&amp;C Committee equally weighs
the achievement of our corporate performance goals and our corporate management objectives in its evaluation of the annual incentive award for each of the named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Apache&#146;s 2011 corporate performance goals and results were as follows: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Adjusted earnings and cash flow are non-GAAP financial measures, as defined in Regulation G promulgated by the SEC. Adjusted earnings is net income (loss) attributable
to common stock adjusted for certain items that management believes affect the comparability of operating results, such as foreign currency fluctuation impact on deferred tax expense, merger, acquisitions and transitions costs, net of tax, deferred
tax adjustments, and additional depletion, net of tax. A reconciliation of adjusted earnings to net income for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011 is contained in item 7 of our Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011.
Cash flow is cash from operations before changes in operating assets and liabilities. A reconciliation of cash flow to net cash provided by operating activities for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011 was previously furnished to the SEC in our
Current Report on Form 8-K on February&nbsp;16, 2012. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Other Performance Measures for Annual Cash Incentive Bonus </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The foundation of our annual cash incentive bonuses is the Company&#146;s achievement of our corporate performance goals and corporate management
objectives. In addition, the MD&amp;C Committee believes that annual cash incentive bonuses are most effective when they are carefully tailored to job responsibilities of individual executives. The MD&amp;C Committee receives input from the chairman
and chief executive officer, who evaluates officers with regional responsibilities on their region&#146;s production, revenue, costs, and other results, while corporate-level officers are evaluated on Company-wide results. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Long-Term Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Board of
Directors believes that properly designed long-term, equity-based incentives align the interests of executive officers and employees with those of the Company&#146;s shareholders and play an important role in overall Company compensation. Long-term,
equity-based incentives are regularly made available to substantially all Company employees to ensure a company-wide ethic of ownership and entrepreneurialism. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Stock Ownership Requirements </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Stock ownership requirements more closely align the interests
of the Company&#146;s officers and directors with those of the Company&#146;s shareholders. Since 2007, we have had minimum stock ownership requirements for our Board of Directors, and in November 2009, we adopted a two-part stock ownership policy
for the Company&#146;s officers. Officers are expected to be in compliance with these minimum requirements by November 2012. For officers who were appointed after November 2009, compliance with these requirements is expected within three years of
their appointment. All of the named executive officers meet these requirements. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The first part of the stock ownership policy requires that
each officer own at least the number of shares of common stock equal to a multiple of the officer&#146;s base salary, measured against the value of the officer&#146;s holdings, based on the average per share closing price of the Company&#146;s
common stock for the previous year. After achieving the minimum stock ownership requirements, each officer must continue to meet the minimum stock ownership requirements for his or her current office. The ownership requirements are: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="92%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="81%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="4%"></TD>
<TD></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" NOWRAP STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Position</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Requirement</B></FONT></TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Chief Executive Officer</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Presidents</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
