<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executive Vice Presidents and Senior Vice Presidents</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">2.5x&nbsp;Base&nbsp;Salary</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Vice
Presidents and Regional Vice Presidents</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">2x Base Salary</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In determining stock ownership levels, the Company includes: shares purchased in the open market; vested shares in
qualified and non-qualified plans; shares obtained through stock option exercises that the officer continues to hold; the vested portion of restricted stock units (&#147;RSUs&#148;) and restricted stock; shares beneficially owned in a trust or
partnership, by a spouse, and/or minor child; and shares held in the Company&#146;s deferred delivery plan. Unearned performance shares, unvested RSUs, and unvested shares of restricted stock are not counted toward meeting the requirements. The
average annual per share closing price of the Company&#146;s common stock is used to determine satisfaction of the above requirements. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">36 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The second part of the stock ownership policy provides that each officer hold at least 15 percent of all
restricted and performance shares he or she receives, net of tax withholding, until such officer retires or otherwise terminates his or her employment with the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Components of Our Equity-Based Long-Term Compensation Programs </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company grants a
combination of RSUs, stock options, and periodic conditional grants of performance shares, the overall value of which is based on a multiple of salary and is targeted so that total compensation is at or above the 50th percentile of the market data
for total compensation amounts. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Restricted Stock Units </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The RSUs awarded to our named executive officers vest ratably over four years, upon vesting allow each grantee to receive one share of common stock for each RSU, and are forfeited if they are unvested and
the executive voluntarily terminates or is terminated for cause prior to the vesting date. These RSUs are typically granted each May to substantially our entire employee population, including our named executive officers (the &#147;May RSUs&#148;).
Each January, the Company also awards conditional grants of RSUs as performance shares, see &#147;&#151; Long Term Compensation &#151; Performance Shares&#148; below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Stock Options </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In May 2011, the Company&#146;s executive officers also received
stock option grants under the 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan (prior to shareholder approval of the 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan). Generally, our stock options: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">are granted to almost half of our employees, including our named executive officers; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">benefit the named executive officers only if shareholders also benefit from appreciating stock prices; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">are granted to the named executive officers in proportion to their base salary; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">become exercisable ratably over a four-year period; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">cannot be repriced or reset; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">have an exercise price equal to the closing price of the Company&#146;s common stock on the date of grant and expire 10 years after grant; and
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">allow for accelerated vesting upon a change of control and a recipient&#146;s involuntary termination or voluntary termination with cause.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The grants of stock options made in 2011 to the named executive officers are reflected in the &#147;Grants of Plan Based
Awards Table.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Performance Shares </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company periodically awards conditional performance shares. Currently, the Company grants performance shares at the beginning of each calendar year under the TSR Program. The TSR Program consists of
contingent grants of RSUs that vest depending on the total shareholder return of the Company compared to that of its peers over a three-year period. If performance thresholds are met, these contingent grants of RSUs will vest over a two year period
following the performance period. If performance thresholds are not met, our employees receive no RSUs under the TSR Program for that year. Prior to adoption of the TSR Program, grants of performance shares were made under the 2008 Share
Appreciation Program and the 2005 Share Appreciation Plan. The periodic grant of performance shares, otherwise known as conditional grants, provides an effective retentive element of performance-based compensation. The periodic grant of performance
shares complements and reinforces the overall compensation program. Each of these performance programs is described below. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">37 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>Total Shareholder Return Program </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In 2009, the Board concluded that a realignment of our long-term compensation program was necessary to provide a compensation program competitive with our
peers against whom we compete for executive talent. Therefore, in November 2009, the Board of Directors approved and authorized the Stock Option Plan Committee, then a subcommittee of the MD&amp;C Committee, to implement the TSR Program. The TSR
Program is part of an annual performance-based incentive compensation program whereby, in January of each year, a conditional grant of performance shares is made in the form of RSUs to substantially all management and senior level professional
employees, including each named executive officer, based on a target percentage of the grantee&#146;s annual base salary determined immediately prior to the beginning of a three-year performance period. At the conclusion of the three-year
performance period for each performance program, a calculation of TSR performance will be made, and the Company&#146;s performance will be directly ranked within each Performance Peer Group (as defined below), resulting in the application of a
payout factor to the conditional grant of RSUs to derive the adjusted number of RSUs awarded. Employees must be employed during the entire performance period and on the date of vesting, and RSUs that do not vest are forfeited. Eligible employees
hired after the date of grant will enter at the beginning of the next available performance period. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The peer companies are determined at the
commencement of each performance period. The peer companies selected for each performance period (the &#147;Performance Peer Group&#148;) are comprised of a larger group of our peer companies than the companies in our compensation peer group for a
given performance period. We use an expanded list of performance peer companies for each year&#146;s TSR Program for the following reasons: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><U>Comparison</U>:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The broader Performance Peer Group provides a more appropriate basis for judging our corporate performance
than the more narrowly focused compensation peer group. The compensation peer group consists, in large part, of companies whose principle business is North American oil and/or natural gas and who are our predominant competition for executive talent.
As approximately 45 percent of the Company&#146;s operations are outside of North America and approximately 45 percent of our production is crude oil, it is more appropriate to have a larger, more diversified peer group to benchmark our corporate
performance. The expanded Performance Peer Group includes many companies we compete against internationally. The overall risks and opportunities faced by this larger group more closely match ours than those faced by the less diversified compensation
peer group. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><U>Continuation</U>:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Because it is not unusual that one or two companies in our compensation peer group may cease to exist
during a three-year performance period, through merger or otherwise, the expanded group provides more stability and longevity to the TSR Program. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><U>Statistical Reliability and Validity</U>:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The larger Performance Peer Group provides a more stable and valid statistical
yardstick for the TSR Program. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The TSR for the Company and each member of the Performance Peer Group is determined by
dividing (i)&nbsp;the sum of the cumulative amount of each company&#146;s dividends for the performance period (assuming same-day reinvestment into the company&#146;s common stock on the ex-dividend date) and the average per share closing price of
each company&#146;s stock for the 60 trading days at the end of the performance period minus the average per share closing price of the company&#146;s stock for the 60 trading days preceding the beginning of the performance period; by (ii)&nbsp;the
average per share closing price of each company&#146;s stock for the 60 trading days preceding the beginning of the performance period. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">38 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:5%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><U>Vesting</U>:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If the Company&#146;s TSR ranks from 1 to 13, vesting will begin on
December&nbsp;31, 2012, with 50 percent of the adjusted number of RSUs vesting immediately, 25 percent vesting as of December&nbsp;31, 2013, and 25 percent vesting as of December&nbsp;31, 2014. If the Company ranks from 14 to 19, none of the target
RSUs will vest. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>2010 Bridge Awards </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Because the TSR Program performance awards granted in January 2010 would not begin to vest, if at all, until the end of the three-year performance period on December&nbsp;31, 2012, on January&nbsp;15,
2010, certain employees, including the named executive officers (except Mr.&nbsp;Farris) were granted one-time bridge awards of RSUs that vested over 24 months. Mr.&nbsp;Farris agreed with the Board that, in light of the RSU grant to Mr.&nbsp;Farris
in May 2008, it was appropriate for him to forego a bridge award. The bridge award amounts were based on a number of factors, including a comparison of compensation levels at peer companies and the responsibilities of the grantee&#146;s position.
The RSUs granted pursuant to the bridge award vested as follows: one-third on January&nbsp;15, 2010, one-third on January&nbsp;15, 2011, and one-third on January&nbsp;15, 2012. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>2008 Share Appreciation Program </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">On May&nbsp;7, 2008, the Company established the 2008 Share Appreciation Program under which, one-time conditional grants totaling approximately 2,773,000 shares of Company common stock were made to
substantially all full-time employees and certain part-time employees of the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The primary purpose of the 2008 Share Appreciation
Program, like the Company&#146;s prior share appreciation plans, was to provide incentives to our employees to work toward significant increases in shareholder value. The conditional grants vested only upon attainment of an initial price threshold
of $162 per share of the Company&#146;s common stock prior to year-end 2010 and a final price threshold of $216 per share prior to year-end 2012. Effective December&nbsp;31, 2010, the conditional grants for the $162 per share threshold expired
because the price threshold was not attained, and those grants were forfeited. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">40 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">
In November 2009, the 2008 Share Appreciation Program was amended to provide that employees hired after December&nbsp;31, 2009, would not be eligible for grants under the 2008 Share Appreciation
Program. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><I>2005 Share Appreciation Plan </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In 2011, the Company issued the final vested installment under the 2005 Share Appreciation Plan, which was established by the Company in February 2005 and approved by the Company&#146;s shareholders in
May 2005. The 2005 Share Appreciation Plan served the same purpose as the 2008 Share Appreciation Program and operated in a similar manner. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Benefits </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>General
Executive Policies </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">As part of their total compensation, the Company&#146;s named executive officers are eligible for a limited number of
benefits, which are designed to maintain market competitiveness. This includes an annual physical examination, cash-value-based variable universal insurance, enhanced long-term disability coverage, 50 percent of health club membership, and continued
contributions to a non-qualified deferred compensation plan once limits are reached in qualified retirement plans. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Use of
Company Property </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company&#146;s operations are spread around the globe, including in locations that present a variety of physical and
geo-political risks. Therefore, for both business efficiency and security reasons, the Board of Directors requires the chairman and chief executive officer to use the Company&#146;s aircraft for all business air travel, unless good business judgment
would require otherwise. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">More details on the above benefits are presented under &#147;All Other Compensation&#148; following the &#147;Summary
Compensation Table.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>COMPENSATION DECISIONS IN 2011 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>The Named Executive Officers </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The following discussion sets forth decisions regarding 2011
compensation for our named executive officers: Messrs. G. Steven Farris, Roger B. Plank, Rodney J. Eichler, Jon A. Jeppesen, and Thomas P. Chambers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">On February&nbsp;22, 2011, Apache&#146;s Board named Rodney J. Eichler as president and chief operating officer and Roger B. Plank as president and chief corporate officer. Mr.&nbsp;Eichler formerly
served as the Company&#146;s co-chief operating officer and president &#151; International and Mr.&nbsp;Plank formerly served as the Company&#146;s president. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Experience and Responsibilities </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Chairman and Chief Executive Officer
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Farris, who joined the Company in 1988, was named chief executive officer in May 2002 and chairman of the Board in January 2009.
His leadership responsibilities include developing sustainable global strategies, recommending and implementing the Company&#146;s capital expenditure programs, developing and maintaining sound business relationships with many of the world&#146;s
major energy companies, developing and maintaining good relationships with the shareholder, investment, and policy-making communities, guiding and developing senior management, and overseeing the Company&#146;s major business and staff units.
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">41 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; direct reports include each of the other named executive officers, except for
Mr.&nbsp;Chambers, who reports to Mr.&nbsp;Plank, and Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen, who reports to Mr.&nbsp;Eichler. Also reporting directly to Mr.&nbsp;Farris are our executive vice president and chief technology officer, executive vice president of corporate
reservoir engineering, executive vice president and general counsel, executive vice president of human resources, vice president of worldwide exploration and new ventures, and vice president of environmental health and safety. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Other Named Executive Officers </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Messrs. Plank, Eichler, Jeppesen, and Chambers have served Apache for a combined 84 years. During this period, each of them has made significant contributions to the Company. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Plank, our president and chief corporate officer, has been employed by Apache for 30 years, and has been instrumental in managing the
financial health of the Company, including management of complex financial matters related to the expansion of the Company into a global enterprise. The scope of his responsibilities has continued to grow as the Company has grown and as the number
of legal and financial jurisdictions in which the Company operates has multiplied. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Eichler, our president and chief operating officer, has been employed by Apache for 18 years and currently oversees the Company&#146;s
worldwide operations. Under his leadership, the Company obtained record production results this year despite facing economic challenges in some of its regions and political upheaval in Egypt, its largest region by production revenue. Previously, he
had responsibility for our international operating regions consisting of Egypt, Australia, United Kingdom, Argentina, and Chile, and prior to that time he headed our operations in Egypt for 12 years. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen, our executive vice president, Gulf of Mexico regions, has been employed by Apache for 19 years. He leads our Gulf of Mexico
operations, which have grown significantly as a result of our acquisition of Devon Energy&#146;s Gulf of Mexico assets and our merger with Mariner Energy, Inc. in 2010. Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen is leading Apache&#146;s effort to develop the Gulf of Mexico
region, including the underdeveloped and oil prone deepwater Gulf of Mexico, where Apache and its co-venturers have recently begun development of the Lucius project. This project is a milestone for Apache, as it is the first major deepwater Gulf
project. Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen was previously the head of all of our Gulf of Mexico operations, which have now grown and been divided into three separate regions (Gulf Coast Onshore, Gulf of Mexico Shelf, and Gulf of Mexico Deepwater).
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Chambers, our executive vice president and chief financial officer, has been employed by Apache for 17 years. He has an exceptional knowledge
of the Company and our industry. Mr.&nbsp;Chambers has been an integral contributor in the Company&#146;s industry trend and acquisition analysis, commodity price analysis, monthly and long-range financial budgeting and forecasting, business segment
and corporate performance forecasting and analysis, investor communications, and hedging strategy. Mr.&nbsp;Chambers successfully led an effort by the Company to reduce its debt by $925 million in 2011, bringing our debt-to-capitalization ratio down
to 20 percent at year-end 2011, from 25 percent at year-end 2010. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Base Salary Actions </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Chairman and Chief Executive Officer </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; base salary for 2011 was $1,750,000. Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; 2011 base salary earnings were slightly above the 75th percentile of market data. Mr.&nbsp;Farris did not receive an
increase in his base salary during 2011 or 2010. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">42 </FONT></P>

<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Other Named Executive Officers </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">To make base-salary adjustment recommendations for the named executive officers other than the chairman and chief executive officer, the MD&amp;C
Committee begins with input from the chairman and chief executive officer concerning the individual performance of each executive and his input concerning the optimal application of the data and policies used (and summarized above) to establish
salary ranges more generally. The MD&amp;C Committee reviews this information and analyzes how the base salary and contemplated adjustments for each named executive officer fit with market data, Company performance, market conditions, and internal
pay parity considerations. In order to ensure that the named executive officers&#146; compensation is aligned with the market and in recognition of the rapid growth and complexity of our organization, each of our named executive officers (other than
our chairman and chief executive officer) received two base salary increases in 2011. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In 2011, in connection with their scheduled salary
review and after reviewing the relative positioning of their salaries against the 2011 Compensation Peer Group, the MD&amp;C Committee recommended and the Board approved the following base salary increases for our named executive officers (other
than Mr.&nbsp;Farris, whose base salary is discussed above): </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Each of Mr.&nbsp;Plank&#146;s and Mr.&nbsp;Eichler&#146;s salary was increased in May 2011, to $825,000 from $700,000. In November 2011, in recognition
of the substantial increase in the size of the Company and their significantly expanded roles within the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Plank&#146;s and Mr.&nbsp;Eichler&#146;s salaries were raised to $900,000 (which is between the 50th and 75th percentile of
the market data), effective as of January&nbsp;1, 2012. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In conjunction with his annual salary review, Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen&#146;s salary was increased from $450,000 to $500,000 in February 2011. Due to the
expansion of the Gulf of Mexico regions as a result of the Devon and Mariner acquisitions in 2010, Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen now supervises three region vice presidents. In recognition of his increased responsibilities and his leadership role, in this
region and throughout the Company, in May 2011, Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen&#146;s salary was increased to $600,000 (which is between the 50th and 75th percentile of the market data). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

the relative positioning of his salary against the 2011 Compensation Peer Group, in November 2011, Mr.&nbsp;Chambers&#146; salary was further increased to $535,000 (which is between the 50th and 75th percentile of the market data).

STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Chairman and Chief Executive Officer </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In recommending the 2011 annual cash incentive bonus
for Mr.&nbsp;Farris to the Board, the MD&amp;C Committee used an analysis specific to the position of the chief executive officer. Because of the </FONT></P>

responsibilities of this office, when setting Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; annual cash incentive bonus, the MD&amp;C Committee assessed the following factors, among others: </FONT></P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">the Company&#146;s multi-year comprehensive performance, the position and strength of the Company relative to peers; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">the level of annual earnings, cash flow and direct lifting costs. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">As stated above, in 2011, the Company achieved record revenues, cash flow, production and year-end reserves. Earnings also increased by 50 percent over 2010 to $4.5 billion. The MD&amp;C Committee noted
that the record results in 2011 were a result of strategic actions set in motion by Mr.&nbsp;Farris and the other members of Apache&#146;s senior executive team over the past several years.&nbsp;Over that period, the Company has focused its growth
on geographic and product balance, a position that many of our peers have stated they aspire to achieve in the future. As a result of our balanced product mix, Apache was able to capture higher price realizations in 2011 when crude oil and liquids
provided 50 percent of Apache&#146;s production and 79 percent of its revenue. This balanced product mix also positions the Company to capture upside potential through a significant increase in either commodity price increase. Furthermore, as a
result of our geographic balance, while North American gas prices deteriorated in 2011, Apache was able to capture higher gas prices in our international regions where our gas realizations increased by 27 percent. Under Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146;
leadership, the Company has achieved this balance while continuing to maintain its conservative capital structure and living within cash flow. In 2011, the Company met its objective to fund exploration and development capital with operating cash
flow and to reduce our debt by $925 million, ending the year with a debt-to-capitalization ratio of 20 percent, down from 25 percent at year end 2010. Also, at the end of 2011, the Company had access to $3.3 billion in available borrowing capacity,
which positions it to take advantage of future potential acquisition opportunities. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Committee also recognized that while Apache has had
record results for 2011, the Company&#146;s stock price has lagged behind many of its peers largely due to the political upheaval in Egypt.&nbsp;Apache&#146;s operations in Egypt constituted 29 percent of the Company&#146;s production revenue in
2011, and because of the political uncertainty in Egypt, the stock price has not reflected the Company&#146;s recent performance.&nbsp;The Committee, however, based its decision on Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; compensation on its underlying principles of
rewarding long-term performance rather than short-term-performance metrics such as total shareholder return.&nbsp;While total shareholder return is a factor in the Company&#146;s equity compensation program, it is not the sole basis for determining
the annual compensation of our executives. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; annual cash incentive bonus was targeted at 200 percent of his 2011 earnings.
The MD&amp;C Committee and the Board considered all of the above factors when setting Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; annual cash incentive bonus without assigning specific weights to each of them. On February&nbsp;7, 2012, the Board,
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">44 </FONT></P>

pursuant to the recommendation of the MD&amp;C Committee, awarded Mr.&nbsp;Farris an annual cash incentive bonus for 2011 of $4,750,000, which was 136 percent of his target. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Other Named Executive Officers </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The 2011 annual cash incentive bonus for the above named executive officers (other than the chairman and chief executive
officer discussed above) was comprised of a corporate performance element and an individual performance element. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The corporate performance
element is composed of the Company&#146;s achievement of its corporate performance goals and corporate management objectives: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Corporate performance goals include objective financial measurements of production growth, reserve replacement, earnings, cash flow, and lifting costs
per boe. Each corporate performance goal represented up to approximately 10 percent of an officer&#146;s annual incentive bonus. For each corporate performance goal, the executive officers could be awarded full credit if the Company achieved the
goal, partial credit if the Company exceeded results from the prior year but failed to meet the goal, and extra credit if the Company over-achieved the goal due to the extraordinary nature of these achievements. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Corporate management objectives include tactical goals for each part of the corporate organization. Each basic corporate management objective
represented up to approximately 2.5 percent of the officer&#146;s annual cash incentive bonus. If the Company overachieved one or more of the basic objectives, or if it achieved one or more of the important objectives, the executive officers could
be awarded additional credit due to the importance of these achievements. The MD&amp;C Committee has discretion in determining the relative success of the corporate management objectives. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">After its evaluation, the MD&amp;C Committee determined that the Company achieved 94.7 percent of our corporate performance goals in 2011 and 121.2
percent of our corporate management objectives. As a result, the Company&#146;s total aggregate achievement of our corporate performance goals and corporate management objectives was 107.9 percent, comprised of 47.3 percent for our corporate
performance goals and 60.6 percent for our corporate management objectives. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The individual performance component was based on the individual
achievement of each executive, as determined by the chairman and chief executive officer and recommended by him to the MD&amp;C Committee. The leadership and management skills of the executive were evaluated. A variety of qualitative and
quantitative goals and performance results were taken into account, such as job responsibility, job complexity, and successful performance of an executive officer&#146;s business units. There was no attempt to quantify, rank, or otherwise assign
relative weights to these subjective factors. The chairman and chief executive officer conducted an overall analysis of these factors and considered the totality of the information available to him. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">45 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">For Messrs. Plank and Eichler, the chairman and chief executive officer qualitatively assessed the
performance of their respective groups, considering 2011 results for various categories, including exploration, production, and drilling, and made recommendations to the MD&amp;C Committee as to the appropriate credit that should be given for
regional achievements. In the case of Mr.&nbsp;Chambers, Mr.&nbsp;Plank and the chairman and chief executive officer evaluated his performance during the year and made recommendations to the MD&amp;C Committee. In the case of Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen,
Mr.&nbsp;Eichler and the chairman and chief executive officer evaluated his performance during the year and made recommendations to the MD&amp;C Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Based on the foregoing, including the Company&#146;s 2011 corporate performance and in light of the compensation decision-making processes and policies described above, including recommendations by our
chairman and chief executive officer and consideration of the performance of the applicable Company regions, Mr.&nbsp;Plank and Mr.&nbsp;Eichler were each awarded an annual cash incentive bonus for 2011 of approximately 115 percent of their
respective 2011 earnings (105 percent of their targets); Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen was awarded an annual cash incentive bonus for 2011 of approximately 80 percent of his 2011 earnings (80 percent of his target); and Mr.&nbsp;Chambers was awarded an annual
cash incentive bonus for 2011 of approximately 100 percent of his 2011 earnings (100 percent of his target). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The named executive
officers&#146; annual cash incentive bonus awards are set forth below and reflected in the &#147;Summary Compensation Table.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Long-Term Compensation Awards in 2011 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In 2011, the Company granted a total of 108,769 stock options and 149,690 RSUs to the named executive officers as a group (including the Company&#146;s chairman and chief executive officer) under the
Company&#146;s 2007 Omnibus Plan (prior to shareholder approval of the 2011 Omnibus Plan). In 2011, Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen did not receive any grants of stock options because in May 2011, the Board awarded Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen with a special retention grant
of 32,730 shares of RSUs, which will vest one-half on December&nbsp;31, 2012, and one-half on December&nbsp;31, 2013. In addition, as a result of this special grant, going forward, Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen has agreed to forego all other equity based
long-term compensation awards. All of the named executive officers received conditional grants of RSUs under the 2011 Performance Program. These conditional grants will vest only upon achievement of certain total shareholder return thresholds over a
three year performance period and will be payable only if the executive officer is an employee at the time of vesting. See &#147;Long-Term Compensation &#151; Performance Shares &#151; Total Shareholder Return Program &#151; 2011 Performance
Program&#148; above. </FONT></P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>149,690</B></FONT></TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>&nbsp;&nbsp;</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>&nbsp;</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>108,769</B></FONT></TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>&nbsp;&nbsp;</B></FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>TAX LEGISLATION RELATED TO COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended, imposes a limit, with certain exceptions, on the amount that a publicly held corporation may deduct in any tax year commencing on or
after January&nbsp;1, 1994, for the compensation paid or accrued with respect to its chief executive officer and its three highest compensated officers for the year (other than the principal executive officer or the principal financial officer). The
MD&amp;C Committee continues to review the Company&#146;s compensation plans based upon these regulations and, from time to time, determines what further actions or changes to the Company&#146;s compensation plans, if any, would be appropriate. It
is the intention of the MD&amp;C Committee for the Company to receive shareholder approval for all future stock-based compensation plans so that they may qualify for the performance-based compensation exemption. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company&#146;s 1998 Stock Option Plan, 2005 Stock Option Plan, 2005 Share Appreciation Plan, 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan (including the 2008
Share Appreciation Program and the 2010 and 2011 TSR Programs), and 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan (including the 2012 TSR Program) were approved by the Company&#146;s shareholders and grants made under such plans qualify as
&#147;performance-based&#148; under the regulations. The Company&#146;s existing annual cash incentive compensation plan, special achievement bonuses, Executive Restricted Stock Plan, and 2000 Stock Option Plan do not meet the requirements of the
regulations, as the shareholder approvals necessary for exemption were not sought. However, these plans operate similarly to prior or other existing plans and are designed to reward the contribution and performance of employees and to provide a
meaningful incentive for achieving the Company&#146;s goals, which in turn enhances shareholder value. No further grants can be made under the Company&#146;s 1998, 2000 and 2005 Stock Option Plans, Executive Restricted Stock Plan, and 2007 Omnibus
Equity Compensation Plan. While the MD&amp;C Committee cannot predict with certainty how the Company&#146;s compensation policies may be further affected by this limitation, it is anticipated that executive compensation paid or accrued pursuant to
the Company&#146;s compensation plans that have not met the requirements of the regulations will not result in any material loss of tax deductions in the foreseeable future. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">On June&nbsp;24, 2011, the Internal Revenue Service issued proposed regulations clarifying that performance-based compensation attributable to stock options and stock appreciation rights must specify the
maximum number of shares with respect to which options or rights may be granted to each individual employee during a specified period in order to meet the performance-based compensation exemption.&nbsp;These proposed regulations would apply to tax
years ending on or after the date final regulations are issued.&nbsp;The Company&#146;s compensation plans currently include this provision. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">47 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Internal Revenue Code section 409A requires &#147;nonqualified deferred compensation plans&#148; to meet
requirements in order to avoid acceleration of the recipient&#146;s federal income taxation of the deferred compensation. The Internal Revenue Service issued final regulations in April 2007 regarding the application of Section&nbsp;409A, which were
generally effective January&nbsp;1, 2009. Prior to effectiveness, companies were expected to comply in &#147;good faith&#148; with the statute, taking note of the interim guidance issued by the Internal Revenue Service. The Company amended several
of its benefit plans in order for them to be exempt from Section&nbsp;409A, while the Company continues to provide benefits through several plans that remain subject to Section&nbsp;409A. The terms of these plans were amended before January&nbsp;1,
2009, as necessary, to meet the requirements of the final regulations. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_24"></A>MANAGEMENT DEVELOPMENT
AND COMPENSATION COMMITTEE REPORT </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Management Development and Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors of Apache Corporation
reviewed and discussed with Company management the Compensation Discussion and Analysis set forth above, and based upon such review and discussion, recommended to the Board of Directors that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in
this Proxy Statement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>All Other Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Officers participate in two qualified retirement plans. The 401(k) Savings Plan provides a match up to the first six percent of base pay and incentive bonus. The Money Purchase Retirement Plan provides an
annual six percent company contribution into the same investment choices as the 401(k) Savings Plan with the exception of Company stock. Additionally, officers can elect to participate in the Non-Qualified Retirement/Savings Plan to defer beyond the
limits in the 401(k) Savings Plan and continue Company contributions which exceed the limits in the qualified plans. The investment choices mirror those in the 401(k) Savings Plan and the Money Purchase Retirement Plan. The Deferred Delivery Plan
allows officers the ability to defer income in the form of deferred units from the vesting of restricted stock units under the Company&#146;s Executive Restricted Stock Plan, 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan, and 2011 Omnibus Equity
Compensation Plan. The contributions into both non-qualified plans are reported in the Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation Table. The Company does not have a defined benefit plan for U.S. employees. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Apache provides U.S. employees with two times their base salary under group term life insurance. Executives receive the first $50,000 of coverage under
the same group term life insurance plan, and the remaining amount to bring them up to two times salary is provided in the form of whole life insurance policies. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Board requires G. Steven Farris to use the Company&#146;s aircraft for all air travel for security reasons and to facilitate efficient business travel, unless good business judgment requires
otherwise. Even though the Company considers these costs a necessary business expense rather than a perquisite for Mr.&nbsp;Farris, in line with SEC guidance, the following table includes the amounts attributable to each Named Executive
Officer&#146;s personal aircraft usage. Executives are not reimbursed for the taxes on the income attributable to the personal use of corporate aircraft. The methodology for the valuation of non-integral use of corporate aircraft for disclosure in
the Summary Compensation Table, in compliance with SEC guidance, calculates the incremental cost to the Company for personal use of the aircraft based on the cost of fuel and oil per hour of flight; trip-related inspections, repairs and maintenance;
crew travel expenses; on-board catering; trip-related flight planning services; landing, parking, and hanger fees; supplies; passenger ground transportation; and other variable costs. Additionally, the value of trips attributable to philanthropic
interests was included, even though they are seen as contributing to the goodwill of the Company. In addition, Standard Industry Fare Level (&#147;SIFL&#148;) tables, published by the Internal Revenue Service, are used to determine the amount of
compensation income that is imputed to the executive for tax purposes for personal use of corporate aircraft. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In addition to the benefits for
which all employees are eligible, the Company also covers the cost of an annual physical and pays 50 percent of health/fitness club membership dues and the full cost of enhanced long-term disability coverage for executive officers. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The Company provides various forms of compensation related to expatriate assignment that differ according to location and term of assignment, including:
foreign service premium, foreign assignment tax equalization, location pay, housing and utilities, home leave and travel, goods and services allowance, relocation expense, and tax return preparation. These items have been broken out separately in
the following table under Foreign Assignment Allowances to reflect the amounts that pertain to Mr.&nbsp;Eichler. Mr.&nbsp;Eichler, as executive vice president &#151; Egypt, resided in Egypt during 2007, 2008, and January to June 2009. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">50 </FONT></P>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(e)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This amount for 2011 includes $21,911 for taxes related to foreign assignment and $750 for tax return preparation. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:3px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This amount for 2010 includes $272,277 for taxes related to foreign assignment and $250 for housing and utilities. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:3px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This amount for 2009 includes $36,466 for relocation allowance and expenses, $31,500 for housing and utilities, $24,877 for taxes related
to foreign assignment, $19,500 for location pay, $14,625 for foreign service premium, $6,182 for goods and services allowance, and $750 for tax return preparation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executives assigned to foreign countries typically incur a change in their overall tax liability because most of the components of assignment compensation that are provided in addition to base salary are
taxable in the United States and in the foreign country. Therefore, the Company&#146;s expatriate assignment policy provides that it will be responsible for any additional foreign or U.S. taxes due as a direct result of the international assignment
and the executive remains financially responsible for the tax which he/she would have incurred if he/she had continued to live and work in the United States.&nbsp;Pursuant to this policy, the Company withheld from Mr.&nbsp;Eichler&#146;s
compensation an amount equivalent to the taxes that would have been due had he remained in the United States.&nbsp;Those funds were used to help pay taxes due in the United States and in Egypt during the period of his foreign assignment.&nbsp;The
Company paid taxes due in excess of Mr.&nbsp;Eichler&#146;s withholding that were incurred as a result of his foreign assignment. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">52 </FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_26"></A>GRANTS OF PLAN BASED AWARDS TABLE </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The table below provides supplemental information relating to the Company&#146;s grants of stock options and restricted stock units during fiscal year
2011 to the Named Executive Officers. There were no stock appreciation rights granted during fiscal year 2011. Also included, in compliance with SEC rules on disclosure of executive compensation, is information relating to the estimated grant date
fair value of the grants. For stock options, the estimated fair value is based upon principles of the Black-Scholes option pricing model. The Black-Scholes model utilizes numerous arbitrary assumptions about financial variables such as interest
rates, stock price volatility and future dividend yield. Neither the values reflected in the table nor the assumptions utilized in arriving at the values should be considered indicative of future stock performance. </FONT></P>

performance in the bottom quartile results in no payout. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On November&nbsp;17, 2010, pursuant to the 2007 Omnibus
Equity Compensation Plan, the Company established the 2011 Performance Program Specifications for all professional and management employees (excluding Egyptian nationals and non-exempt support staff and non-supervisory field staff) who are employed
on or before December&nbsp;31, 2010. These employees, including the executives named in the Summary Compensation Table, were granted the right to receive restricted stock units (&#147;RSUs&#148;), the number of which will be determined and for which
vesting will begin on December&nbsp;31, 2013 based on the Company&#146;s total shareholder return (&#147;TSR&#148;) as compared to a peer group of 18 companies. At the conclusion of the three-year performance period, which began on January&nbsp;1,
2011 and ends on December&nbsp;31, 2013, the Company&#146;s performance will be directly ranked within the peer group, resulting in the </FONT></P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If the Company&#146;s TSR ranks from 1 to 13, vesting will begin on December&nbsp;31, 2013, with 50
percent of the adjusted number of RSUs vesting immediately, 25 percent vesting as of December&nbsp;31, 2014, and 25 percent vesting as of December&nbsp;31, 2015. If the Company ranks from 14 to 19, none of the conditional RSUs will vest. Employees
must be employed during the entire performance period and on the date of vesting. Newly eligible employees will enter at the beginning of the next available performance period. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">TSR is determined by dividing (i)&nbsp;the sum of the cumulative amount of a company&#146;s dividends for the performance period (assuming same-day reinvestment into the company&#146;s common stock on the
ex-dividend date) and the share price of the company at the end of the performance period minus the share price at the beginning of the performance period by (ii)&nbsp;the share price at the beginning of the performance period. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This column reflects the number of restricted stock units granted under the terms of the 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan on May&nbsp;4, 2011. The grant date fair
value of these awards, calculated in accordance with FAS 123R, is based on a closing price of the Company&#146;s common stock on the date of grant. Except as discussed below, such restricted stock units are generally non-transferable, vest ratably
over four years, and no dividends are paid on such units until vested. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(4)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This column sets forth the number of shares of the Company&#146;s common stock subject to options granted under the terms of the 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan.
The options granted under the terms of the 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan are generally nontransferable and become exercisable ratably over four years. The options were granted for a term of ten years, subject to earlier termination in
specific circumstances related to termination of employment, and are not intended to qualify as incentive stock options under Section&nbsp;422 of the Internal Revenue Code. The exercise price and any withholding tax requirements may be paid by cash
and/or delivery or attestation of already-owned shares of the Company&#146;s common stock. The Company&#146;s stock option plans, including the 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan, are administered by the Stock Plan Committee of Apache&#146;s
Board of Directors. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Options granted under the 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan are subject to appropriate
adjustment in the event of reorganization, stock split, stock dividend, combination of shares, merger, consolidation or other recapitalization of the Company. Upon both a change of control of the Company and termination of employment, all
outstanding options become automatically vested so as to make all such options fully vested and exercisable as of the date of such change of control. A change of control occurs when a person, partnership or corporation acting in concert, or any or
all of them, acquires more than 20 percent of the Company&#146;s outstanding voting securities. A change of control shall not occur if, prior to the acquisition of more than 20 percent of the Company&#146;s voting securities, such persons,
partnerships or corporations are solicited to do so by the Company&#146;s Board of Directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The grant date present value is based on the Black-Scholes option pricing model adapted for use in calculating the fair value of executive stock options, using the
following assumptions for the grants made May&nbsp;4, 2011: volatility &#150; 34.47 percent; risk free rate of return &#150; 1.95 percent; dividend yield &#150; 0.47 percent; and expected option life &#150; 5.5 years. There were no adjustments made
to the model for non-transferability or risk of forfeiture. The actual value, if any, an executive may realize will depend on the excess of the market price over the exercise price on the date the option is exercised. There is no assurance the value
realized by an executive will be at or near the value estimated by the Black-Scholes model. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_27"></A>OUTSTANDING EQUITY AWARDS AT FISCAL YEAR-END TABLE
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">The table below provides supplemental information relating to the stock-based awards held by the Named Executive Officers at

per share. On each of July&nbsp;1, 2009 and January&nbsp;4, 2010, 50,000 of the restricted stock units vested. On January&nbsp;3, 2011, 50,000 of the restricted stock units vested, resulting in compensation of $6,051,500. The closing price of the
Company&#146;s common stock on January&nbsp;3, 2011, was $121.03 per share. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The remaining 100,000 restricted
stock units vest ratably on the first business day of each of 2012 and 2013. Upon vesting, Apache will issue one share of common stock for each restricted stock unit, and 30,000 out of each 50,000 shares will not be eligible for sale by
Mr.&nbsp;Farris until such time as he retires as chief executive officer or otherwise terminates employment with the Company. Mr.&nbsp;Farris could elect to defer receipt of all or part of the vested shares and was granted dividend equivalent
payments on the unvested restricted stock units equivalent to cash dividends on the Company&#146;s common stock. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Farris serves the Company pursuant to an employment agreement, dated June&nbsp;6, 1988, under which his base salary as of year-end 2011 is $1,750,000.&nbsp;The
agreement has an undefined term and may be terminated by either the Company or Mr.&nbsp;Farris on 30 days advance written notice.&nbsp;If Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; employment is terminated without &#147;cause&#148; (as defined in the employment
agreement), or if he terminates his employment within 30 days of a reduction in his salary without a proportionate reduction in the salaries of all other Company executives, Mr.&nbsp;Farris will receive, for 36 months thereafter, (a)&nbsp;an amount
equal to his base salary as it existed 60 days prior to termination and (b)&nbsp;50 percent of the maximum amount for which he qualified under the Company&#146;s incentive compensation plan, calculated on his base compensation as it existed 60 days
prior to termination. In the event of Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; death during the 36-month period, the amounts described above shall be paid to his heirs or estate in addition to continuing individual dependent benefits for 60 days.&nbsp;These rights and
obligations would be the same if a termination in either of these circumstances were to follow a change of control. Mr.&nbsp;Farris has agreed not to render service to any of the Company&#146;s competitors for the term of his employment or, unless
he is terminated without cause, for 36 months thereafter. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

stock unit, and 30,000 out of each 50,000 shares will not be eligible for sale by Mr.&nbsp;Farris until such time as he retires as chief executive officer or otherwise terminates employment with the Company. If Mr.&nbsp;Farris is terminated by the
Company without cause and not by reason of becoming disabled or if Mr.&nbsp;Farris terminates his employment for good reason, then all unvested restricted stock units shall vest and the above restrictions shall lapse. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Payments Made Upon Death or Disability </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">In the event of death for Mr.&nbsp;Farris, Mr.&nbsp;Roger Plank, Mr.&nbsp;Eichler, Mr.&nbsp;Jeppesen, or Mr.&nbsp;Chambers, in addition to the benefits listed in the preceding table, payments will also be
made under the Company&#146;s life insurance plan. In the event of disability, these executive officers would benefit under the Company&#146;s disability insurance plan. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="toc300104_31"></A>COMPENSATION COMMITTEE INTERLOCKS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>AND INSIDER
PARTICIPATION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Frederick M. Bohen, John A. Kocur, A. D. Frazier, Jr., and George D. Lawrence served on the Management Development and
Compensation Committee of the Company&#146;s Board of Directors for all of 2011. On November&nbsp;15, 2011, William C. Montgomery was appointed to the Management Development and Compensation Committee. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Kocur, a member of the Management Development and Compensation Committee since September 1991 and a director of the Company since 1977, retired
as an executive officer in June 1991. Pursuant to the terms of an employment agreement in place at the time of his retirement, Mr.&nbsp;Kocur receives health, dental and vision benefits. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence, a member of the Management Development and Compensation Committee since May 1997, is the former president and chief executive officer of The Phoenix Resource Companies, Inc.
(&#147;Phoenix&#148;). Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence joined the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in May 1996, in conjunction with the Company&#146;s acquisition of Phoenix by a merger on May&nbsp;20, 1996, through which Phoenix became a wholly-owned subsidiary
of Apache. Pursuant to the terms of his employment agreement with Phoenix, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence received medical and dental benefits through December 1997. Since that time, he has purchased medical and dental coverage through the Company at full cost.
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">60 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
